column1: 336006;instagram;2018-09-29 10:27:24;FALSE;"the news has been exceptionally hard for survivors in recent months, and particularly for those following what is happening in the us right now. the incredibly powerful #whyididntreport hashtag that was borne of this shared trauma is so important, and globally relevant. reporting rates for sexual violence are low, and so many survivors fear that they will not be believed.

we want you to know: we believe you. we support you. we do not require a police report to access our services, and nor do any rape crisis centres in the uk. we are here to listen, to hear you, and to help you on your journey of recovery. you don't have to face this alone.

i’ve spoken about my assaults publicly,in interviews before. ironically,no one made much of it and it got swept,like most tabu issues,under the rug...small talk.
i’ve been raped twice.

-once in the east village nyc,1981,in a doorway to an building.switch blade to my throat.why i didn’t call the police,i have no idea.i was too traumatized.luckily i only got an std.had to tell my then,live in boyfriend,who did not believe me(he thought i cheated on him)and he broke up with me,double whammy.

-2nd time it happened,i knew the guy.he was at a party in my home.he was the last to leave.punched me hard,several times, in the face&raped me.i thought he was going to kill me.i was so shocked& ashamed that i didn’t tell my friends or mother until 10 years later.
i have “healed” ..i’m left more angry that i didn’t retaliate.
i’ve shared this with my husband&teenage daughters so that they can protect themselves.
i do believe #christineblaseyford
i also am sending love to all of you who have been brave to  post your stories.i thankyou.
#metoo #ibelieveher

i’m not making this about #stopkavanaugh as i never wanted him to have the most important seat in the judicial system to begin with.";;en;#metoo, #christineblaseyford, #metoo, #ibelieveher, #stopkavanaugh;;;;;0;;debimazar;Debi Mazar;;0;False;1239;0;0;20184;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/864516658a986e836492ce7bdc8c8437/5D19969A/t51.2885-15/e35/42423825_888730404659167_91315652365055222_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"#metoo

336015;instagram;2018-09-29 10:33:28;FALSE;"with the terrible actions of the us to degrade and abuse women in politics and the legal system it has reminded me of our own engrained sexism and my own experience in science and engineering.
i live with anxiety partly due to nature, partly nurture.

the battle of having to be ""one of the lads"" to be part of the team. to accept the mysogyny in order to work on site because they won't change for me. to feel intimidated daily when i'm the only female on site. to have to walk around with used sanitary products in my bag because they won't provide bins. to be called aggressive and to be told i'm too emotional or on my period when i try to assert authority. to have been silenced when i spoke up about sexual harassment to the point where i felt i had to find a new job.

i could go on for days, and the worst thing about it is the silence of all these men who say they are ""good guys"". if you are silent, you are complicit. if you don't address mysogyny in your male peers then you are responsible for maintaining the culture.
it is your obligation to speak up to casual sexism as well as when it is overt and abusive.
#metoo #daisybarnard #ibelieveher #womeninconstruction #hivisheroines

way back at the start of my career as an artist i chose to photograph only women, i felt this was my prerogative. so that day it was natural for me to look for women as my subject and i was spoilt for choice! as far as demonstrations go what a stylish, good-looking march it was. the outfits were amazing and the signs were as smart as the women who held them. this wasn’t an angry mob… although we are angry… it was a determined crowd of all ages, out in the best and demanding to be recorded. the collaboration and willingness of my subjects was so energizing for me.

336047;instagram;2018-09-29 11:14:41;TRUE;;"#repost @padmalakshmi with @get_repost
i want to thank each and every one of you that reached out, commented, tweeted, shared this piece with others, and more importantly shared your own stories.

because of the time sensitive nature, given what’s going on, i rushed to write this for the @nytimes without stopping to think of the toll it would take on my own emotional well-being. in the past three days i have been anxious, depressed, nauseous, sobbing and holding on to #littlehands so much and so tightly she is highly annoyed! (she has no idea why and thinks it’s mommy’s hormones.)

but the outpouring has been such a salve, a balm to my frayed nerves and feeling flayed. when you sublimate something for over thirty years, you get pretty good at it. even very close members of my family have been utterly shocked and saddened. my mom has had to deal with her guilt. but she and i have made peace with our history. she, like most parents, has done the best she could.

doing this very difficult thing has been for me a necessary step. i am no longer scared of ghosts. i hope that my story and those of literally millions of others can contribute to how we address this harrowing topic in our culture. so many of you have messaged me with your own experiences and i am truly sorry that we share this trauma. but the only antidote is taking our power back by being as open as possible, and sending young girls and women the message that there is no shame in speaking out.

what happens to a woman’s body should be her choice at all times, and in all cases. we must exert dominion over our own bodies. that what’s at stake here. and that’s why i shared what i did. thank you for your support.
love,
padma

#metoo is this #metoo?

i was in a relationship for a very long time... the better part of my 20s. i loved this guy and took everything to heart- because he was my life partner and all. eventually he would start commenting about my depression (which i have a hormonal issue, and this is a side effect and not anything new or a surprise to anyone), and then he would eventually comment on my weight (i’m goddamn 4’10”)- i don’t mean to qualify this, but i was training for an ironman and was in the best shape of my life... but i was still undesirable in his eyes, and that’s all that mattered to him. and it became what mattered to me.. no matter how many miles i worked that week, i wasn’t lean enough to be desired by my long-term partner.

fuck that. i am a beast that was swimming, running, & biking more than 1% of the population & def more than him. i was jacked (for my body composition [why do i have to quality that]). i lived with a man that excreted toxic masculinity for far too long. he *literally* said to me- “negative reinforcement works better on you, so i’m going to keep doing that”. fuck. that. shit. call your senators, state reps, there is no need for this... we need women in government. we are people.  period.

336066;instagram;2018-09-29 11:36:08;TRUE;;"i don’t play politics, i don’t like it.  whether or not the hearing was ridiculous is not the point.  how long ago it happened is not the point.  to all of you who think all of these women coming forward against their accusers are liars, gfy.  do women lie about being assaulted? yes and it’s a damn shame.  do men lie about being offenders? sure do.  and unfortunately a lot of both times alcohol or drugs are involved.  but that doesn’t make it okay.  yes means yes.  if yes does not happen, there is no consent.  and most of you posting about all this shit have daughters.  go read the stats on their chance of being assaulted.  it’s real high.  and there’s a damn good chance you mother/sister/girlfriend/wife was assaulted at some point also. stop being a pig.  #metoo ❗️repost @fitqueenirene ・・・
i am scared to have a daughter.
i am scared i wouldn’t be able to protect her.
i am scared that one night she might drink a little too much
and trust the wrong person
or feel safe when she shouldn’t.
and if something does happen to her
i am scared that society will try to silence her if she tries to speak up
that they will tell her it was her own fault
and that maybe if she covered up
or didn’t have that last drink
it wouldn’t have happened to her.
because that’s what happened to me.

336088;instagram;2018-09-29 11:54:04;FALSE;"my current cptsd. to predators and their supportive societies.

you don't want to sexualise my body uninvited, regardless of your sex. because this is when i 'bite' with my sharpest teeth, even if i choose not to say anything (unless i see the sense in it). the body is the body, a marvellous mechanism, including the nipples, vagina and the buttocks. keep your objectifying shit in your head, trust me, nobody is interested in your thoughts spoken or glanced.
nudity is not about you, ever. it doesn't belong to you in any way. get down, get down, it's all in your head.
i'm not going to hide or expose any of my parts to fit into your undersized cave while mine is cavernous beyond your imagination.

a person who rose from an assault, his/her/their dignity and pride, will throw you in your place at a frequency you can't explain and can't stand up too either - you are too little, too rotten to withstand a real strength. no words needed.
it is the power of humiliation, intimidation and abused privileges hurled back at you by your own ignorance.
did you do your best to make up for the irreversible? just for your own peace, mine wasn't broken.

336098;instagram;2018-09-29 11:58:20;FALSE;"bewitching; trans edition
power of women everywhere reliving our trauma & emanating our collective energy is turning the tide.
make no mistake, we believe survivors... 1 in 3 of us are the survivors.

we have tapped into the pain & power all at once, bewitching the nation. i don’t post about all of my trauma, but i do the work on the regular with women+ who identify and need a good set of ears from someone who knows. i’ve tapped into the collective energy & set a course for self-care, collective care, & creative healing. most of this year has been rough, but as october approaches i’m committing to owning my power & using it to be of love & service to others. i will not sit back or remain invisible. i will speak up when about injustice, i’ll go heart first into hard conversations. our hearts generate 60 times more electromagnetic energy than our brains do, so listen to that power and lead with that. time and again our limited brain power will fail us. it’s only basis is our own limited life experiences & perspectives. allow yourself an opportunity to grow when you investigate the perspectives of others empathize with others experiences.
listen to your heart... she knows

336099;instagram;2018-09-29 11:58:52;FALSE;"bishop franco cannot be held accountable for something his body did: pope

bishop franco mulakkal, a catholic bishop of the syrian malabar church, was recently summoned by the pope in the vatican. the bishop is accused of raping a nun from kerala on multiple occasions and it was only recently that the victim came out to speak against him.

bishop franco wrote a letter to the pope seeking relief from the vatican and expressing his distrust in the indian judiciary system. after thoroughly analysing his case, the pope has issued a statement in his support stating that bishop franco cannot be held accountable for something his body did.

while explaining his statement, the pope said: “we cannot identify ourselves just as a physical form because life’s much more than that.” in order to make sure these incidents don’t happen frequently, the pope has now updated the rules to becoming a bishop. the strict set of new rules shall contain (but not be limited to) basic guidelines for bishops on what to say and how to deal with a situation if one gets caught after molesting or raping a nun.

336107;instagram;2018-09-29 12:02:04;FALSE;"i wrote this book to give other abuse survivors a simple roadmap to begin their healing process. many books on this topic are quite complex, but this cuts the fat to go to the meat: how can i heal. .
this is for male and female survivors.
how can i speak to a new lover about my sexual triggers?
how can i ever forgive my mother for beating me like that?
how can i ever have a relationship and trust anyone?
why is my money situation so messed up? .
you will find some answers here and more importantly practical tools, especially if you download the additional free workbook i offer inside of this book. .
this book is for survivors of physical, mental or sexual abuse. you will find the practices apply for many types of experience. .

i found i had to go to many sources to piece together why so many different areas of my life were not working the way i wanted them too. i realised that my current relationships, and my money issues and my body image were all linked to my low self esteem. .
and when you shift your core self? everything else changes for the better. .
i pray it serves you, please share this post xx
link in bio, or find on amazon: jay diamond: abuse to abundance.

336108;instagram;2018-09-29 12:02:05;TRUE;;"this is so terrifying. i’m going to court cause i finally found the strength and courage to engaged charges against my ex narc and violent boyfriend. i have many proofs but still i don’t know if it’s gonna be enough since we live in a society where people don’t feel concerned about anything if it doesn’t happen to them. #repost @whywomendontleave with @get_repost

this. is. wrong. period. i wish that no one ever had to go through this. going through this is hell. there is a reason victims don't report abuse, especially sexual abuse. i told the police my husband raped me, i didn't expect anything to happen.  i was sent down to the hospital to have a rape kit done. it was one of the single worse experiences. first i had to wait for hours for a nurse trained to do the exam to show up. hours. when she showed up she was cold, rude and short with me. the rape exam is extremely invasive. i had already been violated in so many ways already. i choose to end the exam. we had sex. we were married.  i was forced. it was his word against mine. i was fortunate that i had taken pictures of the physical abuse i had endured over the years. even though i didn't report it to the police (i was too afraid) i took pictures,  showed the date in the photo with a newspaper, printed the photo out and kept the photos in a safe location at a relative's house.  i was able to use those photos in court for my restraining order.  document everything. everything! it's so important.  facts, and proof are necessary.

336111;instagram;2018-09-29 12:02:39;FALSE;"two days ago with a quivering voice, i heard dr. christine blasey ford admit she was terrified and proceed with her testimony anyway.  i have always been in support of the me-too movement, i have shared my own story. but something about her courage made me want fight for those who havent. the memories of my own little world of abuse arose. the heart beat. the agony. the weight and shame of sexual abuse is enormous.

its happened more than once to me. from age 4 to 16. in momentary awkward ways that made me feel embarrassed and small. it's happened in catastrophic ways that left me sobbing with a sense of shame that sat in my stomach for years. my abuser wasnt a stranger, acquaintance, co-workers, he was my grandfather, also a pastor who led a thriving mexican church. i thought we were friends, buddies, i even convinced myself all this was how he loved me.⠀

well i reported it, unknowing that i would the day i was questioned by cps, ....even though my entire family lived in denial, as well as the entire independent fundamental baptist world around me. my culture then blamed me, and i also blamed myself. only two people fought for me then...and have steadily stood by me through the years. (thank you alan and yvette latta) ⠀

i do not say any of this as a victim but as a survivor and fighter. each time i get back up from this rage, a wound is healed, and i learn how to love and trust again. its been a life long journey of healing and trust.

to all the survivors- you're not alone. although the world might try to deny, accuse, attack, berate and belittle- i hear your story, i believe your truth and i stand with you. courage is contagious. thank you to all of the hundreds of thousands who speaking up and speaking out today.

surely we've all seen the name dr christine blasey ford dominating our news cycles and our social feeds. how many of you watched her testimony?
i did, and it gave me chills.

much like anita hill did many years ago, dr christine blasey ford saw a dangerous and abusive man about to be appointed to one of the most powerful positions in the us, and she decided the right thing to do was to tell the truth.
her truth was that when she was 15 years old, this ""man"" sexually assaulted her and she managed to escape before he raped her, all while his friend laughed and watched on.

much like in the case of anita hill, dr ford's life has been turned upside down by her honesty. she and her parents have been subjected to constant abuse and accusations of ulterior motives, to the point that they have had to leave their homes and she has security details.

if you haven't watched dr ford's testimony, please do. she is quiet and polite, and yet immeasurably powerful in her testimony. she has become the voice of so many that have long been to afraid to report or have had their accusations dismissed. many women have spoken about their own assaults for the first time as the result of dr ford's tremendous bravery.

perhaps this time we will truly listen. perhaps this time she will be believed. perhaps this time her being believed will have long lasting consequences, not just for this case, but for all the cases in which the truth of victims is dismissed or minimised.

i am sick of feeling ""lucky"" that i have not been raped or subjected too major sexual assault. even in writing that i feel my minimisation of the all too common ""minor"" assaults i have been subjected to. enough is enough.

336138;instagram;2018-09-29 12:26:05;FALSE;"saw this tweet posted by what is probably a “liberal” account. most likely re-posted by someone as a gesture of what i imagine to be some form of solidarity with #christineblaseyford historic hearing. but when i saw this it operated as a one liner that became an unintended personal trigger. whether it’s online or irl social media can either enrich or narrow our singular points of view. i can not directly live in someone else’s shoes- but because of the openness and willingness of friends, strangers, and public figures who use social media to educate and share their truths- i can challenge myself to learn how to widen my own scope. finding both “corroborating and exculpatory evidence” that allows me to also keep my privileges in check. •

people are dying and suffering everyday in ways we do see and in ways we don’t- which relates to the mental/physical/public health crises in this country (including homelessness/poverty). we literally hear about everything from tragic stories to micro aggressions from marginalized voices everyday. and on different levels, people choose to care and people also callously choose not to care that “the system” continues to be broken ( or designed the way it was intended) for so many period. this image made me think of erica garner and her story. while not directly a #metoo narrative the way people would prefer, it is about forms of activism and the disproportionate tolls it takes on those who struggle to be heard in relation to accountability. dr. ford answered more than once that when deciding to come forward that she was continuously weighing the cost/benefits until both the press flooded her regular life (even so far as her mistaking a reporter for one of her students in her classroom) and a leaked letter made it difficult not to. garner, who continued to seek justice, challenging the same system (like thousands if not millions of others in this timeline) ultimately came at the expense of her health. i thank @rachel.cargle for recently sharing an article about activism/self care which helped to enrich my own understanding about these correlative struggles. •

336143;instagram;2018-09-29 12:26:59;FALSE;"i don’t know who’s house it happened at or even what year it happened. i don’t know if i got there before everyone else or after. i don’t know how i got there or how i got home over 8 miles away (at the age of 15). my life time friend doesn’t remember any of this ( and the other 3 people i said were there testified under oath they don’t know anything about this). i have a fear of flying , but have no problem jet-setting all over the world while on vacation. i’ve been on airplanes more in the past two months than most people in a year, but my fear is completely legit.

i don’t know who paid for my hotel and polygraph test( the afternoon of my grandmothers funeral, or maybe it was the next day, who knows). and guess what? i flew there. oh and that polygraph, it was only two questions, neither of which were about kavanaugh. but hey, i passed so that’s all that matters. and my phd in psychology definitely, in no way, helped me with it or my testimony today.

my friends on the beach encouraged me to continue contacting the media with my story (because we were running out of time). i can’t name them, so we’ll just call them beach friends. yet while giving such great advice, none were willing to be character witnesses. meanwhile, judge kavanaugh had hundreds of character witnesses step up in a matter of days.

my lawyers, out of the kindness of their hearts, are helping me for free yet i have a “needed” gofundme page that currently is sitting at $1,000,000.00 i’m so desperately in need of help there’s even a second gofundme. i promise though i’m not getting anything out of my testimony, that money is just going to cover my expenses.
i’m super smart. i have a phd and i teach graduate students. i know lots of big words, but it should be totally believable that i don’t understand basic questions.
i was the only person in the united states that didn’t know congress agreed to come to me instead of me going to dc. they really do care about my flying phobia after all.

i sat here the other night telling my husband that every single woman i know has experienced some form of assault or harassment, that the #metoo movement didn’t go away, it just got so deafening because we all realized the sheer scale of it. i told him of just one experience that i have never forgotten and never told anyone about. i told him of other experiences too, and just how common they are. i’ll be raising two boys of my own... and while i had envisioned having a little goddess to shape into a warrior i realize that perhaps getting the chance to help guide and shape two men who will know the difference, who will know consent, who will not just watch, but stand by women demanding change is just as important. and i truly pray that by the time they are fathers they won’t have to fear for their daughters safety, or tell her that her skirt is too short, or have this same conversation with their sons. change is coming. good has to win.... even if the road is long.";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;thequillcollective;The Quill Collective;;0;False;4;0;0;13;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/c47ef546ffcdf8e7e4ad399675c21590/5D1FDBB6/t51.2885-15/e35/41660935_682602955457731_4302326210808771924_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"as i sit here... i had to write something, share anything... i can’t turn to hate. i want to but i won’t. because love doesn’t win that way. we don’t win that way.

336159;instagram;2018-09-29 12:44:25;FALSE;"who do you believe? ☀︎
an extremely personal piece. -

i was constantly harassed by someone i knew when i was very young. i did not understand what was going on completely at that time but i knew it wasn’t right. it wasn’t right. i never told anyone because i felt like it was my fault. it wasn’t. it isn’t. it never will be.

perpetrators are not usually psychopaths seen in broad daylight. this man was the best guy everyone knew, had a family of his own, daughters of his own and he dared to lay his hands on me. it’s not always black and white. it never is. -
thank you for reading, sweet souls. hope you’re having a great day / night xo

i was constantly harassed by someone i knew when i was very young. i did not understand what was going on completely at that time but i knew it wasn’t right. it wasn’t right. i never told anyone because i felt like it was my fault. it wasn’t. it isn’t. it never will be.

perpetrators are not usually psychopaths seen in broad daylight. this man was the best guy everyone knew, had a family of his own, daughters of his own and he dared to lay his hands on me. it’s not always black and white. it never is. -
thank you for reading, sweet souls. hope you’re having a great day / night xo

336171;instagram;2018-09-29 12:49:33;FALSE;"i didn’t share my #whyididntreport story because it has been told over and over from survivors of sexual assault...sexual violence....sex predators. energy has been intense & triggering these last few days take much need care of yourself.

i believe you. i believe you all. it was never your fault. it was never what you wore,what you said, what you did or didn’t do. you were never bad or disgusting for what happened to you. you were not a problem for speaking up.you deserve to be heard,believed,and you deserve to heal. i’m sorry if these past few days are a reminder of just how much further we have to go to recognize the power dynamics & harms perpetuated against the marginalized. a culture created & upheld by the patriarchy that places doubt on victims while passing the burden of proof onto us. ;;

i believed it was my fault too.i was too nice, my clothes, or something anything.twice. survival was suppress and ignore. no one told me what consent was. no one told me what a violation to my body would look or feel like. all i was told about sex was true love waits. i internalized it all...sinful,bad,disgusting girl,and no matter what it was me. i’ve spent alot of my adulthood healing,undoing a lot of sexual trauma,and overcoming sexual shame because of sexual assault and because of what i was taught.

with all that’s happening i will continue to resist against a society that makes excuses for the harm it supports against our bodies. a society that says those who speak their stories are trouble makers and ruins lives. fuck dat ole ass patriarchal, elitist ,respectability ,sexist, mythological bullshit. ::
to all survivors... especially all womxn...bipoc survivors ...may we no longer be a prisoner to our traumas,may

we heal, learn to trust our bodies again, be empowered sexually again,and feel safe again...and when or if you ever feel ready to use your voice/share your story...don’t be afraid to speak your radical truth...& make mf trouble. we love you all. we stand with y’all. may the mother’s & ancestors wrap you up in infinite love & care.
(art @kendrickdaye - tweet @blacklivesmatters )

336186;instagram;2018-09-29 13:01:04;FALSE;"you don't have to be trafficked to be a victim of sexual violence. 17,700,000 women have reported a sexual assault since 1998. . . these numbers make my heart so heavy and even heavier with the knowledge that some of these women include our friends, family, co-workers and ourselves. .

freeleaf is at work to bring healing and restoration to so many women who, maybe like you or someone you know, have been deeply hurt by sexual violence. we empower them to know they can choose courage over comfort and share their experience so they can start the healing process. .
the amazing thing about the #metoo movement is that a huge conversation is happening to reshape the way we see sexual violence and bring resources and healing to individual women (and men!). .
if you or someone you know has been sexually assaulted, there is zero shame in sharing your experience so you can get the help you need and hopefully see justice brought to your situation! .

336190;instagram;2018-09-29 13:01:47;FALSE;"71/100 ::why i didn’t report:: i was violated so deeply, so completely, i didn’t know i was a person who needed help, really i didn’t know i was a person at all. growing up with extreme abuse i could not fathom any intervention in what felt like my deserved life sentence of suffering. my hiding and shame grew with me. the older i got the more powerless i felt, the more horror that i still could not defend myself. my denial grew deeper to protect me from my ever growing devastation.

my abuse occupied a separate sphere of reality. i had no words to describe it, i had no voice to say it, cutting my breath my truth sat heavy in my throat, anything that escaped my lips was watered down, a strangled whisper. i was doused in poison.

abuse robs you of your trust in yourself. sexual assault is a wound so deep it knocks all the wind out of your depths and leaves you spun and gagged. it’s so warped and ugly it makes you believe there isn’t a soul on earth who has endured such wicked darkness, writhing in a web of horror and disbelief you withdraw, an alien in your own life.

a child, an adult of any age can be drawn into this wordless world. such a reality does not include reporting it or getting help. such a reality is only concerned with survival. “why did you wait so long?” “he would never do something like that” “you must be confused” “why didn’t you scream” “why didn’t you get help”

many survivors can’t speak about their abuse until they are strong enough—when i finally spoke every person in my biological family called me liar. i had to wait 30 years to be strong enough to absorb that inevitable violence.
i walked through this darkness. i walked through this fire. i see you. i believe you. you are not alone. we are an army of strength and we are beautiful.

hold tight, this exposure is so hard—but we are turning the tide, we are revealing a dark underbelly of our society to be reckoned with. one day our daughters will not know this pain. one day the effects of trauma will be in our common language and understanding. one day when a person says they were raped they will always be supported to healing instead of subjected to scrutiny.

336193;instagram;2018-09-29 13:02:41;FALSE;"after the week we’ve all experienced,
politically, personally, and
exhaustive psychological as well,
i thought it just appropriate enough
to share these other pics from the last show
i did at uptown underground; may’it rest in peace;
with @boytoychicago (and photos by
@peterserockivisuals; thank you, babe). a simple piece about my own traumas
with sexual assault and rape as well.
with all this said: i hope that we can all
give all survivors; especially the women
and doctor ford herself, some space to breathe
and hold them all up high and give support

i believe you #drford. i believe you because it happened to me and i don't think i would have had the courage to go through what you went through yesterday.

336216;instagram;2018-09-29 13:16:45;FALSE;"// what difference does it make?
i asked myself before writing this.
what difference does is make if i say, #metoo?
i think it is obvious.
we are in this together.
in some way or another, the majority of us have experienced sexual harassment, assault, rape or unwanted touching at some point in our lives.
it has become the norm.
it has been acceptable for entirely too long.
we have been blamed for it happening in the first place.
we then get asked why we didn’t say anything sooner?
how it has effected us? in what ways?
as if we are expected to bare our souls, our innermost pain and shame to validify the truth.
our truth.
why is it others’ place to judge or question the validity of your experiences? your pain? your shame? your embarrassment?
why are people so quick to brush off one’s pain as if it does not matter? call them a liar?
do people ever stop to think about how difficult and traumatic it is to even admit the things that have happened to you, let alone speak out loud about them?!
now more than ever am i feeling the weight of it all.
after hearing dr. ford’s testimony, i am reminded of my own personal experiences.
things that have happened in my life that have effected me more than i think i even realize.
i have rarely talked about these moments for the exact reason she did not.
fear for being judged, unsupported, called a liar or simply to ‘just get over it.’
i have buried my feelings + memories of these experiences for a very long time.
after hearing her powerful testimony, i too have relived things that have happened to me, as many of us have had to do.
for the same reasons as her + many other women, haven’t said a word for years because i too did not want to be embarrassed, blamed or shamed for them.
the first time i said something, i was 20.
i was blamed for putting myself in the situation.
the second time i said something, i was 22.
i was told the person ‘didn’t mean it, he was just having fun.’
i’ve never said anything again.
now more than ever do we need to come together, support, listen + care for one another.
authentically.
honestly.
with our whole hearts.
why did it have to come to this for us to support +
love one another?

336218;instagram;2018-09-29 13:17:05;FALSE;it is north america’s dark, open secret that native women are far more likely to be raped, and far more likely to be murdered.
no justice. that is the constant cry from friends and families of victims as countless cases are left unresolved and ignored.
marita growing thunder, a 19-year-old murdered and missing indigenous women (mmiw) activist from montana, has experienced lack of justice – five times.

in the early 2000s, marita’s aunt died. although yvonne’s death was officially recorded as an overdose, marita claims her aunt had been beaten. “all her fingernails had been pulled out. she was unrecognisable when we put her in the coffin. her body was black and blue and swollen.” marita also suggests there were four unrelated deaths in her family which police did not investigate. her father’s aunt, henry, her grandfather’s sister, shirley k, and two female cousins that her mother grew up with.
this is not a problem with one cause, nor is it one that is going away. therefore any attempt to move towards a solution must recognise how terrifyingly deep the international crisis of mmiw runs.
given the complicated and tense mesh of federal, state and tribal law – as well as entrenched racism towards indigenous people across north america – cases continue to fall through the cracks.
read more here:
https://www.independent.co.uk/news/long_reads/native-american-women-missing-murder-mmiw-inquiry-canada-us-violence-indigenous-a8487976.html

336223;instagram;2018-09-29 13:18:24;FALSE;"today (my birthday! 😊) at around 7am mst  the #moon (the subconscious ego) in #gemini activates a grand trine in the air signs with the sun (the conscious ego) in #libra, and mars (the acting ego) in #aquarius. (swipe for the chart.) the element of air is, among many things, about #connection. each of these 3 planets are fundamentally crucial in terms of their representation as aspects of our #psyche (#ego, id and #willpower) and in this instance, each one is joined by a very important #goddess. .

the moon is joined by #juno, (aka hera, the #queen of heaven/wife of zeus) who deals primarily with committed #relationships and the difficulties that often arise within them, like infidelity and jealousy. #lilith was the original #woman and the original #feminist. especially in this dance she's been doing with mars recently, she deals with refusing subservience and thus leaving #partnerships that no longer serve us (or patterns in them that no longer serve us.) the sun is joining ceres (aka demeter - the great mother, nurturer/sustainer of humanity) who deals with themes of loss and return. the alignment of these three important #feminine archetypes along with the moon (the fundamental yin/feminine archetype) occurs just after the #kavanaughhearings, interestingly. .

336227;instagram;2018-09-29 13:20:04;FALSE;"#1in5women will or have experienced sexual violence in their life.
with national #domesticviolencemonth approaching, we wanted to take a moment to say #hertruth is #notyourassumptions.
#ibelieveher! who cares how long it takes her to say “#metoo!” i #trusther #basicmemoryfunctions.
#sheissomeone! #sheismorethan a sister, mother, daughter, or wife.
how dare you ask “why did you wait so long?” - “#whydidyoustay?” - or “how do you know it was he?” october is also #antibullyingmonth, #believesurvivors and stop harassing these #bravewomen!

as sara erdmann stated “i will never understand why it is more shameful to be raped than to be a rapist.” it's time to #endsexualabuse. every 98 seconds an american is sexually assaulted yet the all seeing eye and blind eye of justice always seems to overlook the #testhermony of #resilientwomen.
in case you missed it: “#shessomeone!” we have no room for #rapeculture, beyond a shadow of a doubt, we #believewomen. case and point: #whatifgodwasaher?
would you still mistreat her? would you still deny her truth?
when over a dozen women come forth with the same accusation, would that be enough to be considered beyond a reasonable doubt or would you still want more proof?
in a world that silences women, you gotta #supportsurvivors when they speak up without fear of reproof.
here's the naked truth: the system is filled with men that raped women protecting men that raped women all the while of putting the women who've been raped on trial.

who cares how many drinks she drank? who cares how good she looked in that outfit? a women does not have to be modest to be respected. when did her sex appeal become an open invitation?! drinking is not a crime, rape is! hell yeah she looks hella sexy, yet still her body is not yours to defile!

dear women, i adore you… not for your fabulous physique or wiles, i adore your propensity to push through in this patriarchal society that perpetually attempts to push you down, i adore you for your ability to cry at night yet greet each day with a smile. -stevie #artisactivism #poem

because the only way to educate them is to give them access to information .
she is 9
she asks questions
she wants answers
she wants to know what her rights are
what will effect her life
who will effect her life
she wants to form her own decision .
all i can do is give her an open door to ask questions, form opinions and listen to all sides of the story. .
when asked today she said:(direct quote)

i think he shouldn't be a supreme court judge ,because even if we don't have proof yet that he actually assaulted mrs. ford. the way that he acts and talks to people, is not the way i want a judge to be in a supreme court."" .
expose your children and then listen to them!
@dortomysoul

336241;instagram;2018-09-29 13:23:00;FALSE;"i couldn’t count on all your fingers and toes the amount of times from the age of 21 and under i allowed someone to make me believe that their anger, their fury, the screaming and verbal assault, including physical reactions were somehow my fucking fault. dare i say to the point where i believed i must’ve deserved it.

this is where we do our girls wrong. the years spent saying things like “oh boys just being boys”, “ he’s just a passionate man, when he calms down he’ll apologize” or “are you sure you didn’t do anything to set him off like this?”. well time is up, because i will help build the concrete my girls stand on so that when they are in a situation where somebody decides to be toxic and leslie knope forbid abusive they know for a fucking fact that it’s a reflection of the individual themselves and not their fault. i teach them kindness daily but that it’s also not their job to get in the way of someone who is determined to destroy themselves. i teach them that they are worthy of respect and love and kindness and helpfulness and to be treated as such by anybody they allow in their lives. such as their peers, employers, their family and especially whomever they choose a partner.

it’s a new world and this generation of young women are not here for this shit. we’re here to tear it the fuck down. i stand here (well, with the help of my cane or walker at least) ready to do what i can to take the stands needed, educate others and listen to anyone who needs help to make this a world better suited for my girls. as @glennondoyle said “we will now become strategically and relentlessly disobedient”. 🔥👑🔥 #metoo #timeisup #handicapable #nevergiveup💪";;en;#metoo, #timeisup, #handicapable, #nevergiveup💪;@glennondoyle;;;;0;;chronicwho;DeAnna Gross;;0;False;2;0;0;24;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/55f3b4a22a04fe8098e7da0dac57fc7f/5D140356/t51.2885-15/e35/42346065_696797667364613_2986300803949610651_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i couldn’t count on all your fingers and toes the amount of times from the age of 21 and under i allowed someone to make me believe that their anger, their fury, the screaming and verbal assault, including physical reactions were somehow my fucking fault. dare i say to the point where i believed i must’ve deserved it.

336252;instagram;2018-09-29 13:35:37;FALSE;"🔻jay paul, a talented professional photographer, @jaypaulphoto took this photo of bob woodward, famed investigative reporter, author, and esteemed editor at the washington post @washingtonpost.

🔻mr. woodward has gone on to author 19 books on 9 #presidents. he’s won 2 #pulitzerprize #awards, among many other #awards for his work.
🔻a film adaptation of their book, #allthepresidentsmen was produced by #robertredford @robertredford who also starred as #woodward.
#dustinhoffman played #bernstein.

🔻she told jay that they loved it and asked if a #print or #digital file could be purchased?
jay responded that he’d be honored to give them his material for their personal use.
🔻a day later, the #washingtonpost contacted jay paul to hire him for a #photojournalism project that they had planned in richmond.
🔻both men are such #gentlemen! in this day and age of #metoo and #whyididntreport it’s important to recognize the wonderful men in our lives that are honest, decent, and generous.
🥂cheers to all of them and their fathers and sons!!!!
🔻bob woodward has also been portrayed in #wired and the man who brought down the white house. #themanwhobroughtdownthewhitehouse.

their image, their voice.
black history month series
2/28 “i was born on the island of dominica in the caribbean and raised in the bronx, nyc from the age of 4.
at the age of 7 i was raped and thereafter, sexually molested. i was verbally abused and spiritually beaten down from the age of 8 to 16.

it was as if a war was being waged upon me on every level and i had no protection.  god brought to me countless angels which included one in the form of beethoven’s 5th symphony.  in this music is my story. it spoke directly to me and said marie-claire,  you can make it.

with the help of two great therapists and a strong will to survive, i made it through. after years of severely stuttering from trauma, i discovered my voice, and singing became my saving grace.  it brought me so much joy, it brought me healing and it brought me peace.

i strongly believe in the telling and sharing of my story because it is healing.  i believe that my story could help others going through the same thing. it has taken a tremendous amount of strength and forgiving to get to this point and at 48 years old, i now feel finally ready to share the gift of my contralto voice with the world, —unapologetically, unashamedly and with love, so much love.”
— marie claire giraud  48 years old.

336283;instagram;2018-09-29 13:53:41;FALSE;"""kavanaugh is going to get confirmed, we all know that. a lot of women will be very angry. some might even take to the streets. but this won't be the tipping point. there won't be a tipping point, there never is. there will just be the subterranean lava flow of women's anger - slow, blistering, savage and inexorable. we'll go to bed angry, we'll get up angry, we'll drink our coffee and fix the kids' breakfasts angrily, we'll drive thru car line and to work angry, our male colleagues will ask each other if we're on the rag, we'll eat silent lunches with rage and we'll pick up groceries on the way home with vengeance on our hearts. we'll kiss our partners and our kids goodnight wrathfully. we'll cry hot, silently screaming tears in the middle of brushing our teeth. we'll go to bed angry. we'll get up angry... nothing will seem to change for you. but the mother of a 32 year old  man will suddenly snap at him to ""grow up!"" when he complains that he's pretty sick of frozen dinners lately. that quiet chick 3 cubicles down will show up out of nowhere and tell a gathering of dudebros that she'll report them to hr if they don't shut up. they'll call her a bitch under their breath as she turns around, but she won't care. the teenage daughter will ask her dad if he'd still find it funny if she was the punchline in his favorite joke. he'll scold her for talking back and look at his wife, who will look back and say nothing. another daughter will say nothing to her father - ever again.

the anger will shift, seismic but unseen. before the lava used to burn us to ash on the inside. it's bubbling over now. enough of us have ripped open our bodies to let the boiling soil of our lives out that the heat itself causes fires. sure, you can put one or two out at a time. a single flame is easy to catch. but the lava is elemental and everywhere. kavanaugh will be confirmed. and in less than a generation he'll be a petrified ash fossil, frozen in a rictus of agony in the new pompeii. nothing will seem to have changed, until it's too late. the lava of our anger is going to cover the earth and bury you."" -audra alexander

336291;instagram;2018-09-29 13:55:42;FALSE;"""can you be the woman that i want""

am i the woman who you always wanted? is my skin light enough for you? do i have good hair? does my style reflect the way you believe a woman should dress? do i have an attractive face and a toned body?before you answer, allow me to tell you how different opinions have affected me throughout the years. it started as a girl where family members, friends, and acquaintances shared their ideas of what beauty is. for some reason, i had a difficult time achieving several of their standards. as a result, i struggled to understand what beauty is, and it negatively affected my self-esteem. for years, i desired to achieve the standards of someone else. when others did not acknowledge or see my beauty, it affected how i felt in regards to myself. honestly, i did not always believe i was beautiful. now in my 20s, i realized i could not satisfy everyone's standards. what one person considered to be beautiful, another saw it as unattractive. i decided to define beauty standards based on my happiness and what allows me to stay true to myself. it is not always smooth, especially when there is constant pressure around you. however, i started learning that there is no point in being the woman who you always wanted if i am not the woman that i desire. *
model: brianna plummer
photography by: @moemaureen

336316;instagram;2018-09-29 14:08:57;FALSE;"my article on instituting a sexual harassment code of conduct is out in this month's print edition of dj mag now. .

as we have seen over the last few months, weeks and even days, sexual harassment remains one of the most harmful and challenging issues of our time. it's currently dividing american government and society, and has at times torn at the fabric of the dance music community. .

though i have never experienced sexual harassment firsthand, i have come to learn, as many men have, just how pervasive it is in the lives of the women we love. with this in mind, i asked women what they thought should be done to curtail harassment and discrimination on dance floors and in the workplace of the electronic music industry.

women like meg wilhoite from female:pressure were incredibly helpful and patient in helping me understand this issue in so many new ways, and for that i'm incredibly grateful. and the women of the we have voice collective—who created the sexual harassment code of conduct for their jazz community—were immensely helpful in guiding me through their process in creating the code. and carly wilford of sister collective, who bravely spoke to me to help me understand the issue as part of the wider discussion around mental health in electronic music. i could not have written this without them. .

as midland recently said, ""this is a very good time for men to step back and listen to women and their stories."" that's what i have tried to do here, and will continue to do in the hopes that we can soon see real change. thank you for reading. .

336317;instagram;2018-09-29 14:08:59;FALSE;"and really deeply, truly, i am over the passivity of good men. where the hell are you? you live with us, work with us, make love with us, father us, befriend us, brother us, get nurtured and mothered and eternally supported by us, so why aren’t you standing with us? why aren’t you driven to the point of madness and action by the rape and harassment, degradation and humiliation of us? - eve ensler ~

i started following, reading, and being in awe of eve’s boldness in my early 20’s, when i myself was trying to understand some events in my life and felt small. i dragged my best friend and my boyfriend at the time to several events when i first came across her. the full article is in my bio and i recommend you click it and read it. it’s powerful and important during these evolving times. ~

column1: 336322;instagram;2018-09-29 14:11:03;TRUE;;"deep bow of gratitude to dr. christine blasey ford. the amount of fear she must be feeling to voluntarily walk into the fire, in order to speak her truth...to have to relive her trauma over & over again...is unimaginable. it's like a modern day witch hunt, except for literal fire burning her at the stake, it is lies, ignorance, disbelief, scorn, lack of empathy, chauvinism, objectification, and some f'ed up slander of a biblical text that men have the right to ""own"" women & do to their bodies what they please, irregardless of the consequences. she is standing up against insanity. millennia of being unable to reason with the unreasonable. dr. christine blasey ford and every single person (female, male...all genders) who have spoken up, from privately confiding in a friend to public forums, open themselves up with the risk of being abused again...emotionally & verbally...they risk being told by others that they are the insane ones & that they are less than, that they must have provoked it or actually really wanted it since they were dressed ""inappropriately."" they risk being told their truth is not valuable. it takes bravery to stand up & speak your truth just in day to day situations...i.e in a board room voicing a vision you see for your company that no-one else does. but it is an extreme act of courage...it is heroic...to voice being sexually abused & risk being violently attacked again through the lack of respect & compassion of the toxic & entitled patriarchy. to everyone who has ever spoken out loud their truth & those who do not feel safe enough to speak up, i believe you, i bow to your strength & courage for continuing to live, you are still here & thats audacious. i see you & you are so worthy, you are enough & there are many people, myself included, fighting to right the unspeakable wrongs you have endured. to create a world where the only thing insane is not believing someone's truth or right to have control over their own bodies.
#believesurvivors #ibelieve #metoo #togetherwerise #timesup #bethechange #speakup #lovewins #lovewillprevail

336323;instagram;2018-09-29 14:11:14;FALSE;"i am one of those women in the #metoo movement. a survivor who had a brief reminder this week about my past, my experience and my story of sexual harassment which took place 13 years ago.
it happened during my first year of university. there was no witness and no material evidence. he was a friend. i never thought it would happen to me.
i wondered who would believe me. i wondered who i could trust. i wondered what i did wrong. i wondered how people would react.
i did report it.
within a few weeks after it happened, i became bipolar, went through periods of depression and developed a sense of generalized anxiety.
it was traumatizing. i felt violated and uncomfortable. i felt scared and unsafe. i walked around the world in fear. i felt alone.

some women are brave enough to talk about it. other women have no idea what it is like to go through something like this. it may not be trending, but the unpublicized stories and mental health of women of colour matter too.
many minority women, immigrant women, women of colour and young girls who are victims of abuse suffer alone, in silence. they deserve our support; not our judgement.
i eventually found hope, healing and happiness. i regained my confidence and learned to trust the world again.
becoming a mother of two little girls has made me feel more empowered to share my experiences as a south asian woman and as a mother.

336325;instagram;2018-09-29 14:11:35;FALSE;"in today’s ask kelsey i speak about what to do when your fears, worries, and concerns take over. when you’re not just a little upset, but you are starting to spiral out of control.
you may not even know why. you may just feel a sense of panic and be on high alert for anything that might bring you harm, real or imagined.
from the politics in the united states to the #metoomovement to our own complicated personal lives, its easy for our old patterns of fear to take over.
if you find yourself steeped in anxiety, do your best to love yourself in that state.
your state of panic is not a call for judgment and it is not a reason to beat yourself up.
if you are humming with anxious energy, it is a call for more love.

336329;instagram;2018-09-29 14:12:16;FALSE;"for someone awakening to the trauma of his or her past:
for everything under the sun there is a time.
this is the season of your awkward harvesting,
when the pain takes you where you would rather not go,
through the white curtain of yesterdays to a place
you had forgotten you knew from the inside out;
and a time when that bitter tree was planted
that has grown always invisibly beside you
and whose branches your awakened hands
now long to disentangle from your heart.
you are coming to see how your looking often darkened
when you should have felt safe enough to fall toward love,
how deep down your eyes were always owned by something
that faced them through a dark fester of thorns
converting whoever came into a further figure of the wrong;
you could only see what touched you as already torn.
now the act of seeing begins your work of mourning.
and your memory is ready to show you everything,
having waited all these years for you to return and know.
only you know where the casket of pain is interred.
you will have to scrape through all the layers of covering
and according to your readiness, everything will open.
may you be blessed with a wise and compassionate guide
who can accompany you through the fear and grief
until your heart has wept its way to your true self.
as your tears fall over that wounded place,
may they wash away your hurt and free your heart.
may your forgiveness still the hunger of the wound
so that for the first time you can walk away from that place,
reunited with your banished heart, now healed and freed,
and feel the clear, free air bless your new face.

-john o'donohue";;en;;;;;;0;;thewatershedfarm;Melissa Bennett;;0;False;3;0;0;25;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/69ddfaa638fc4d2dde38583cc9bce004/5D21C0A8/t51.2885-15/e35/41557291_1950460705041427_96602561144958581_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"for someone awakening to the trauma of his or her past:

336344;instagram;2018-09-29 14:20:57;FALSE;"i've read women's comments. yes, women! who think a survivor has to relive her experience a certain way to actually be truthful, to be traumatized. they expect them to cry, to be overly emotional...or it's fake, it's rehearsed, it's calculated. she can't be successful (clearly, not traumatized) or a psychologist (she knows how to play the system and she's very calculating in how to manipulate, they say). she can't ever smile or show joy (she's faking it, it's not real, it's all a plot).

look at me. i don't cry anymore about my trauma (unless i'm in my own healing session). i am successful and i will continue to be successful in all my endeavors because i refuse to give those perpetrators and cowards any more of my power. i studied psychology to understand myself,  to understand others, to heal myself, to heal others, to make sense of the fucked up shit that has happened in my life and countless others.

have you ever been to a funeral and seen someone smile? why do they smile? often we recount positive, uplifting stories and memories of our deceased loved ones. so yes, even in the face of trauma, in fact especially in the face of trauma, we can smile! because there's hope, there's life on the other side. .

336352;instagram;2018-09-29 14:22:49;FALSE;"those who continue to underestimate me, #fuel me.
those who think they know me,  know what i choose for them to know.

i am a shameless #survivor.  the key word is not survivor as i once thought.  the power didn't lie in my ability to survive. the power came from my ability to realize that i am not ashamed of being #raped by a low life, out of control loser like tsgt keith alan snyder, also known as @dontrattlethecage ... his actions don't define me.  my actions define me.
i am #strong,  where he is weak.
i am #confident,  where he is insecure.

336369;instagram;2018-09-29 14:27:10;FALSE;"it takes a whole lot more than courage and bravery to speak on the accounts of being sexually assaulted or raped.
trust me, it is easier said than done but here i am finally speaking about my own sexual assault, my truth.

i have repressed these memories so deep to the point i cannot recall the aftermath details. a high influx of mixed emotions rise as my mind vividly goes back to my mother’s master bathroom. seeing him there standing behind me inspecting every inch of my body with his coke-bottle glasses. that grin, that stupid grin i wanna slap out of his face. the belt, the belt he held in one of his hands . tears, silent tears flowing rapidly down my cheeks. hands, my two shaken hands desperately attempting to cover my full breasts and genital area.
blanked-out! remember! can’t remember! memories, my memories fade away, fade away through years of suppression.
name, his name was moises jerez!
a christian, a god-fearing man, a spiritual grandfather, a pastor - a devil in disguise!

based on the current events and my post i hope more victims and survivors muster the strength to speak up.  share your stories, demand justice and prevent this from happening to other children/teenagers. allow your story to serve as a potential prevention guidebook. parents/guardians i implore you to please think twice before entrusting your children to a friend/family/church/sports/etc. .
✊🏽 bravery is contagious ✊🏽 .
thank you #metoo movement and dr. #christineblaseyford for inspiring me and giving me the courage to finally speak out! .

336376;instagram;2018-09-29 14:34:28;FALSE;"you can look at the top players in the comedy game (#kevinhart, #kattwilliams, #mikeepps) and see that even at the highest level, there's brutal competition. now imagine what it's like for the thousands of would be and upcoming #comics who are competing for opportunities.
add to this this the fact that opportunities are further limited accross #race and #gender lines. (in both directions)
now layer the dynamics between bookers and promoters.

as if that wasn't enough, even in the final moments before taking the stage, it's not uncommon to get approached by audience members threatening to #heckle you and call you out if you fail to make them #laugh.
so, why would anyone want to be the court jester when the world is so quick to be off with your head.
cause we know something.
we know that #fear of public speaking is considered the number one fear among a societies population. yet, we do it in the most hostile environments.
we know that even though some people can't wait to for an opportunity to catch you slipping, most of them secretly imagine themselves on stage garnering the attention.

and we know the power of the spoken word can change the world. let's not forget it was #hannibalburess, a #comedian, that set fire to #billcosby and the #metoo movement. the effects of his performance are directly impacting #brettkavanaugh, the #supremecourt nominee as we speak. think about that for a moment........ in a world where #freedom of speech is not so free, and constantly under attack, comedians continue to maintain a greater freedom of expression, to mock and to criticize.
comedians keep the society in check. and with mainstream news outlets pushing headlines as opposed to real information, comedians remain one of the few sources of the cold hard, #unfiltered truth.
oh. as for the photo. a wonderful young lady kept interjecting during my set so i took a knee in protest.

336397;instagram;2018-09-29 14:39:17;FALSE;"this woman is incredible. she has endured a wave of despicable hate and anger. why? because she spoke out against appointing the man who assaulted her to the us supreme court.
i've been keeping a bit quiet because i'm not american but you know what? screw it.
there is an epidemic not just in the us, but throughout the world. it's called rape culture.
throughout the entirety of recorded history there have been stories of mistreatment and dehumanization at the hands of men. there have also been stories of the women who rose up against it.
however in the past millennia it seems that no matter how many steps we take as a society the world refuses to move forwards in its treatment of women.
just look at the poisonous attitudes that are so pervasive in our society that we are conditioned to believe are normal; ""boys will be boys""
act like a lady""
he's only mean because he likes you""
what were you wearing""
you shouldn't have been drinking""
you shouldn't have been in the park alone""
why didn't you come forward before""

oh, and i am an able bodied, mentally capable white woman. i face none of the additional bullshit thrown at the disabled, the mentally challenged, the trans community and women of colour. i am fucking privileged in this shitstorm of behaviour.
we as a society, we as a united world need to address these attitudes. things need to change. and as the #metoo movement and now dr ford have demonstrated, we are ready and willing to fight for it.
sorry not sorry for the rant. i have a lot of thoughts on this topic.

because of her bravery, i can say through tears and through perseverance that it wasn’t okay then and it isn’t okay now.

i’ve waited awhile to say anything about recent events. as a female survivor of non-sexual, violent assault and non-violent sexual assault there is no other answer but to learn how to effectively defend yourself.
the groin kick doesn’t always work. telling someone to back off doesn’t always work. come learn what does. •

shaan saar is a safe environment with incredible, intuitive, compassionate and phenomenally trained instructors. i’ve been to a lot of women’s self defense courses. they’re sales pitches or packed with creeps. oh yeah, some instructors make a point of trying to be physically intimidating toward women. so instead of calling them on their bullshit and complaining i made sure that our company @shaansaar would be different. •
come see us tomorrow at the rosen jcc in dr. phillips (orlando) and learn why. it’s a free 2-hour workshop appropriate for all females ages 13+ so you have no excuse.
no more complaints because things won’t change until we do.

336412;instagram;2018-09-29 14:47:24;FALSE;"one year ago, i shot the cover of between the stitching on this very field in new hampshire with @ericsnyderphotography, a field that our beloved skyler chased his double a dreams on. as i stood alone on this particular diamond of dirt wearing a jacket that was once considered uniform to him, i envisioned the stadium as if it were packed on a midsummers night that promised post game fireworks. i found my old self in the noise of the imaginary crowd behind home plate.

what a lonely road it is for a weary soul. that poor girl. she wears his messy attitudes and his flimsy masculinity with nothing but a smile. sad girl, i wish i could tell you then what i know now. i know you don’t want to leave him, but it’s time to go. release your grip. he won’t catch you but believe me it will bring you home. .

336414;instagram;2018-09-29 14:47:57;FALSE;"if you’ve been a victim of trauma, sexual assault, rape, abuse in any form i believe you. i stand with you. i see you. i hear you. i’ll fight for you. i love you.

do i believe something must be done & need to change? absolutely. do i believe using our voices to spread judgment, blame, hate, and shame about men as a species is the answer? absolutely not. separating men from women or women from men - separates us as humans. we are not separate. strip us down to bones and energy and we are all one. both masculine and feminine are so importantly equal. and both live within each of us.

i’m always asking myself “how can i live from my highest self” especially when i feel someone else has wronged me. and that answer is always; living, walking, and speaking through love. not the love we’re taught in society. not the one with conditions: “i’ll love you only if you do _____, i’ll love and accept you only if you don’t do ______.”
true love doesn’t have conditions, and it’s one of the hardest practices. it is also the most powerful force on this planet. it is how we can heal. it is how we can create change. .

this does not mean that we lie down, accept things that harm us, or don’t stand up and rise. it means we do it in a way that is out of love not hate. unconditional love. it means we see other people as ourselves and stop separating by gender, race, or even beliefs. the evil in this world is like a fire, spreading and burning everything it touches. lashing out in hate and judgment is like air to the flame. all of us are being burned. not just the ones we hate. it will only feed more hate, more judgment, more suffering. love is like water, washing over the flames and smothering them, putting them out, and nourishing the soil so that something new and beautiful can rise from the ashes. .

fall in unconditional love with yourself. see others through a lens of love without conditions, and watch how the world changes. if we truly want to create change, we must stand up and rise from a place of love. a place of our highest selves. a place where the suffering we’ve endured can no longer spread, because it can no longer survive. .

column1: 336417;instagram;2018-09-29 14:48:33;FALSE;"i never really thought about the word ""triggered"" meant until i saw this comment (and i'm mostly paraphrasing): so many women are coming forward ""crying assault"", & i'm not saying what happened to them ""wasn't wrong"", but i think it's ""taking away from women"" who were actually raped. .

let me tell you why i wasn't ""truly, genuinely and violently raped"": the first time, he broke into my house while i was in the shower. when i came out of the bathroom in a towel he was standing outside he door waiting for me. he forced me into the bedroom, bent me over, facedown, on the bed & while he was trying to pull my towel off, i managed to grab my phone & hit call on the first number i could get to & started screaming. he stopped, but on his way out of the room he got so mad, he punched a hole in my bedroom door.

the second time the same person tried to rape me i wasn't home alone. my children, who were very young at the time, were upstairs asleep. he had me pinned on the floor with all his weight on top of me & had already ripped my pants off. when i realized he wasn't going to stop, i got desperate and started screaming my son's name, hoping that if he woke up & came downstairs, my attacker would stop & leave. it worked.

are my experiences any less important or traumatic because i wasn't actually raped? thousands of women & men coming forward with stories like mine are often times the reason people who were raped have the courage make their assaults public. don't ever dismiss or insinuate that someone's trauma is less than or invalid or in some way hurting the cause because it wasn't as bad as someone else's. a person that would say something like that has either never experienced assault or thinks it's no big deal. everyone deals with it differently. some people convince themselves it's normal or not a big deal. others need therapy the rest of their lives.
i got lucky. i was able to stop my attacker. i didn't have nightmares or depression or suicidal thoughts. does that mean my story shouldn't be heard?

of course, until very recently, i was in denial. i still can't believe it actually happened. **cont'd in the comments**⬇️";;en;;;;;;0;;lady__dmc;Destinee;;0;False;4;0;0;15;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/0f3f1617d275f52b66d06a175e45d5a8/5D192AF1/t51.2885-15/e35/41468632_166608777589838_6381807445057438361_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i never really thought about the word ""triggered"" meant until i saw this comment (and i am mostly paraphrasing): so many women are coming forward ""crying assault"", & i am not saying what happened to them ""wasn't wrong"", but i think it is ""taking away from women"" who were actually raped. .

336418;instagram;2018-09-29 14:48:35;FALSE;"it’s been a tough week, friends. the supreme court hearings have been so painful to listen to; it’s exhausting hearing the experiences of women/survivors being ignored. ⠀
it’s also always a little hard on my mental health as the days get a little shorter and the mornings get a little darker. ⠀

throughout this week, i’ve been trying to focus on bits of light to look forward to: long happy dinners, exciting new photography projects, lovely meetings with inspiring clients. but it’s still been hard.⠀
i’m carving out a bit of time for myself this weekend and i’d love some suggestions for recharging. how do you all balance caring for yourselves when things are hard in the world around us?⠀

336420;instagram;2018-09-29 14:49:32;FALSE;"i’m going to leave this here. —

to the men who’ve cat called me on the way to or from the gym. to the people who’ve honked horns or slowed down in their cars when i’m dressed up for a night out. to the inequality in every area of life. i will not forget these times. we all need to do better. —
i believe survivors. i stand with survivors. i’m here for you. i’m listening. —
we should all be filled with rage, anger, and deep sadness for what has been happening not just this week, but for years and years. —

336424;instagram;2018-09-29 14:50:06;FALSE;"excerpt from “#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women”

i never told anyone. let me repeat that. i never told anyone. not my parents. not my best friend. not the police. not a doctor. because i couldn’t accept it. even though inside my soul was literally crushed and i felt dead. even though i knew it was wrong. even though i logically knew i was raped, i wouldn’t allow myself to accept that reality. i wouldn’t allow myself to say it. saying it out loud would make it real. i couldn’t come to terms with it.
my latest project is called “#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.”
i am still collecting stories. submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthor@yahoo.com.
all stories will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-sexual harassment -rape/assault -sexual, emotional, or physical abuse
-stalking
-gender discrimination
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing my own stories i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well along with the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.

with something that i’ve pushed away. it was late june 2018. i received a text from my ex boyfriend. he was leaving for the air force in a couple of weeks and wanted to say goodbye to me. it was almost 10 pm and pitch black outside when i met him outside of my house. i was 16. weeks from 17, the age of consent in my state. but i was not the age of consent yet. i was 16. he was 19. we walked to the small lake about 5 minutes from my house. we sat on a bench. we were just talking. he suddenly kissed me. he grabbed me and held me against him so i could not pull away. i tried to pull away. i couldn’t. he was so much stronger than me. i kissed him back hoping it was enough to satisfy him. he finally pulled away and asked me to have sex with him. i told him no. he begged me. over and over. i continually denied him. he again held me against him and kissed me. he slid his hands down my shirt and grabbed my breasts. i used all of my strength to pull his hands away from me several times but he continued to kiss me and grab my breasts. i finally got him to stop because by that time it was 10:45 (curfew in our town was 11). i told my best friend what happened and that i was fine. i thought i was okay. it didn’t matter to me. i barely thought about it. dr. blasey ford came forward so bravely. she was 15 when she was assaulted by an upperclassman boy. i was 16 when my 19 year old ex boyfriend assulated me. i want to tell my story without being asked what i was wearing (because my revealing tank top allowed him easier access) or why i went with him. what happened to dr. ford was not her fault. what happened to me is not my fault. seeing my own family victim blame has forced me to relive what happened. it’s forced me to feel the anxiety that i didn’t before. it’s forced me to face it. but i will not let it define me. thank you, dr. blasey ford for giving me the strength to share my story.;;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;theboricuafeminist;Izzy one of my favourites

this work is dedicated to all female authors. it is known that the world of art, like many other branches of social life, belongs to men. men write, men embody, men choose what is brilliant, what is not.
what is it like in this world for women authors: writers, poets, screenwriters and directors? no wonder the last massive movement in defense of women's rights
#metoo appeared in the creative environment. how does it feel to not be taken seriously only on the basis of gender?

creative people burn in their work, and therefore any negative for them is almost fatal. any criticism can finish, any refusal is a blow. and how many women were disappointed in their talent after the first refusal or criticism. how many were told that their place is in the kitchen. and so the talent goes into the deep underground and the masterpieces lie in a pile on the table. brightness and passion vanishes from such women`s lives but boredom comes, then melancholy and bitter regret for their fate.

find the strength not to give up your gift, do not allow anyone, especially yourself to put an end to the implementation of the purpose. write in the comments on what figure on a ten-point scale you now feel recognized and implemented.#paintingoftheday #contemporaryart #conceptart #londonart #valeriyanikuta #ukartist";;en;#MeToo, #contemporaryart, #conceptart, #londonart, #valeriyanikuta, #ukartist;;;;;0;;valeriyanikuta;Valeriya Nikuta;;0;False;6;0;0;132;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/b51dfd110457bbd477ff6131d890d49f/5D0AB524/t51.2885-15/e35/41766320_327822681360322_1685267876026454308_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"“unsent” 2017 ❗️sold❗️

column1: رومن پولانسکی «من متهم می‌کنم» را کارگردانی می‌کند

آی سینما: رومن پولانسکی فیلمساز سرشناس و جنجالی قرار است فیلم جدیدش را درباره مردی که می‌کوشد شهرت و حیثیتش را بازگرداند، کارگردانی کند. آنچه اغلب رسانه‌ها درباره این خبر برجسته کرده‌اند آن است که این نخستین فیلم پولانسکی بعد از آغاز جنبش#metoo و تلاش برای منزوی کردن و مجازات مردان  متهم به آزار جنسی است.
پولانسکی سال‌هاست که به اتهام تجاوز جنسی از آمریکا فراری است و حتی چند سال پیش در سوییس دستگیر شد تا به آمریکا بازگردانده شود، اما نهایتا آزاد شد.

به گزارش هالیوود ریپورتر، او می‌خواهد فیلم «من متهم می‌کنم» را درباره زندگی واقعی سروان آلفرد دریفوس بسازد؛ یک سرباز فرانسوی یهودی که به جاسوسی برای آلمان متهم شد و محاکمه‌اش در سال‌های آخر قرن نوزدهم در پاریس به نقل محافل تبدیل شده بود.

why would farmers hurt their animals? the simple answer is because they can. there should be no surprise here, the whole system is built on oppression, cruelty, suffering and death.
so many times people say that farmers treat their animals like family. unfortunately this is not an isolated incident.
on september 24, 2010, billy joe gregg, jr., a worker at conklin dairy farms caught on hidden camera during a mercy for animals investigation maliciously abusing cows and calves.
♦️was the farming community outraged?

yes, but for the wrong reasons.. after this documented abuse, many farmers began to write articles about how farmers needed to be more diligent, and do a more thorough background check, in order to make sure that they do not hire an undercover investigators. if you treat the animals like family then why the need?♦️
