i think today’s headlines really explain why men and women don’t come forth with trauma all the time. can you imagine...being violated mentally, sexually, physically? can you imagine being hushed by the person who did it? or worse...not being hushed but sitting there wondering if it was your fault, should you have been more aware, had less to drink...what could you have done differently? it’s gut wrenching.

it took literally until i was a normal family to realize that the things i endured were wrong. i didn’t know everyone’s dads didn’t threaten to kill them. i didn’t know that using posters to cover the holes in the walls where he put our heads through the dry wall wasn’t normal. i just thought “when kids are bad, we are punished” because my friends all feared getting in trouble like i did. but they feared losing pizza night or sleepovers. they feared losing privileges and chore money. they didn’t fear for their lives....their faces....their bones.

so i look at this woman, sitting in front of a room full of men who already don’t believe her...telling them about her most painful memories. she’s not doing it for a lawsuit or money. she’s years past that option. she’s doing it because she believes she is protecting a nation from a man in power...because she was not protected against that man in power and it ended in her ultimate nightmare.

who cares if she slept with 5 men a week? who cares if she is as a drunk? who cares if she wore short skirts? you telling me all of that matters sounds the same as “kaylin, you shouldn’t have failed your math test” or “kaylin, you should’ve let him hit your brother” or “kaylin, you shouldn’t have been the oldest young lady in that house” ...telling me her choices allow him to violate her is not only insulting but re-opens those wounds. if you believe her or not...questioning her publicly is hurting every victim out there.

next time you’re in public look to your left count three women. then look to your right and count three women. on average...one of them has been sexually assaulted. look at them. take note of the ones who are moms. the ones who are big sisters.

336467;instagram;2018-09-29 15:03:19;TRUE;;"repost from @giantloopmoto using @repostregramapp - we ❤️ strong, independent women. check out all of the amazing giant loop riders we tagged in this repost from @lonerucksack : “so many … risk so little, they spend their lives avoiding danger. i’d risk everything to get what i want.”⁣
—game of thrones⁣

for all the women who’ve had to endure ‘go back to the kitchen and make me a sandwich’ jokes. for all the women who’ve ever had a man crawl into their bed in the middle of the night in a hostel dormitory. for all the women riding motorcycles who’ve had to endure monologues from men with less experience who’ve decided to place themselves in the role of instructor. for all of the women who’ve been told it’s not safe to sleep outside alone— for all the women who’ve been told ‘it’s not safe’ by people who continue to prop up misogynist cultural norms and men that continue to make it so. for all the women who have been followed home, trolled online, and shouted at walking down the street. for all the women who’ve been told ‘he’s harmless’ to invalidate their experiences. for all the girls who have been told to stay silent, and haven’t been protected by older women. for all the women with male family members and male friends who couldn’t be bothered with the women’s march, or the kavanaugh hearings, because it doesn’t directly affect them. ⁣
for all the women— i stand with you. ⁣

336473;instagram;2018-09-29 15:04:32;FALSE;"them demons, those things most of don’t even feel comfortable discussing with other. what’s crazy is this whole “me too” movement happens to every single one of us female and male (including my self) no one should take this lightly, no one should brush this shit under the rug. this needs to be talked about!! sexual harassment, molestation and rape is not funny. i understand that dark humor is the “in thing” but g realize that most women don’t know whom to turn to weather it be a relative and or a close friend. be sure to check on your strong friends, also try to surround your self by positivity and amazing energies.
mental health is important!! i know i will be fine, it takes baby steps and i can honestly admit that i’ve been suffering from ptsd from my trauma 💔 it’s mentally frustrating and exhausting.
things to remember while going through these difficult times: •breath
•journal •meditate
•run
•detox

336529;instagram;2018-09-29 15:30:31;FALSE;a little morning perspective… ****trigger warning: sexual assault**** who will love me? …i asked myself after i reported being sexually assaulted to the police. my body now tainted and disgusting.
who will love me? …i asked myself after they found him. because i reported my case to the police too late, the predator was found sexually assaulting another woman. clearly it was my fault.

who will love me? …i asked myself sobbing on the bathroom floor of the courthouse. it was the worst deposition the prosecuting attorney and counselor had seen. both apologized to me for not making it stop.

who will love me? …i asked myself trembling hysterically in the witness stand.  subpoenaed as a character witness in another victims trial i was at a loss for words. the judge chose to announce a recess.

who will love me? …i asked myself as the defense attorney openly discussed my sexual history in front of the jury. his final plea, “miss mcdaniel laid on her back to receive (insert predators name here.)” my heart sank.
who will love me? …i asked myself as i found out his church and family paid for an attorney to appeal his 12-year to life sentence. surely his god did not love me.
who will love me? …i asked myself after my boyfriend said he had been advised to “make sure” he can “deal” with my trauma and me… for-ev-er. he could not deal.
who will love me? …i asked myself as i hid parts of my life from family and friends. once i lied to my cousin about needing to study. she had no clue i was in a different city prepping for trial.

and we wonder why victims wait days, months, and years to speak up and report?! it is the road less traveled because it is treacherous to navigate. personally my mind began to play tricks on me by believing all of the horrible accusations made by attorneys’. i experienced spiritual trauma, a wound so deep it is hard to find words to explain.  my body was objectified and humiliated in front of a jury and pews of strangers. navigating how to build meaningful relationships in the midst of it all was near impossible. this is why #ibelievesurvivors  #isupportsurvivors #metoo";;en;#ibelievesurvivors, #isupportsurvivors, #metoo;;;;;0;;love.melissa.ann;Melissa Ann

336531;instagram;2018-09-29 15:30:53;FALSE;when i was writing my high school memoir in 2008, i wanted to include the story of a survived assault and the aftermath that followed— my fear in speaking up because of threats and the false and hurtful stories he spread— but a female at the publishing house told me it “wasn’t original enough.” she said it was a story that “every girl has lived to some degree,” that we’ve all heard it, and that for those reasons we should leave it out. but it happened to me. it impacted me. and if so many other women—and men— have experienced the same thing, shouldn’t we be talking about it more, not less? so i fought to keep it in. what they ultimately published was a watered down version. years later that boy— then a grown man— cornered me at a reunion and asked if he was the one in the book. he just didn’t know “what the fuss was about” and hoped i would be “over it by now.” thank you to everyone who speaks up and out and who uses your voice so that others don’t have theirs taken away. thank you to all the brave and beautiful souls who are out there fighting. 🌹 this lovely art by @tylerfeder is available to buy from her etsy shop, with all proceeds going to @rainn 🌼💫 together we can make a difference. 🦋#speakupsaturday #drchristineblaseyford #believesurvivors #useyourvoice #metoo #timesup #neverthelessshepersisted why would farmers hurt their animals? the simple answer is because they can. there should be no surprise here, the whole system is built on oppression, cruelty, suffering and death.
so many times people say that farmers treat their animals like family. unfortunately this is not an isolated incident.
on september 24, 2010, billy joe gregg, jr., a worker at conklin dairy farms caught on hidden camera during a mercy for animals investigation maliciously abusing cows and calves.
♦️was the farming community outraged?

yes, but for the wrong reasons.. after this documented abuse, many farmers began to write articles about how farmers needed to be more diligent, and do a more thorough background check, in order to make sure that they do not hire an undercover investigators. if you treat the animals like family then why the need?♦️

336545;instagram;2018-09-29 15:43:38;FALSE;"i know i make flowers and that my followers like it when i post beautiful images. but today i don’t want to post flowers. i want to post this bc i want everyone to remember that we elected the man who said this shit to the highest office in our country. the presidency. and yesterday the senate judiciary committee voted kavanaugh up one step closer to being sworn in as a supreme court justice with a lifetime appointment to the most powerful bench in our country. kavanaugh has been accused of sexual assault. (he was after all nominated by the pussy grabber who has been accused of sexual misconduct by over 20 women.)

we watched his accuser testify publicly before the committee. and by testify, i mean be essentially prosecuted by a woman the republican committee members hired to interrogate and attempt to discredit dr. ford as if she were on trial! dr. ford bravely shared her account of the attack under oath as she felt it was her civic duty to do so. then it came time to question kavanaugh. not only was he was combative, sarcastic, smug and disrespectful, he refused to clearly answer whether or not he had ever been blackout drunk and refused to quantify his drinking during the period in question. he also refused to state emphatically that he would welcome an fbi investigation which makes zero sense if he truly desires to clear his “good name”. additionally, the committee failed to subpoena the only man who dr. ford named as a witness, mark judge.
this is unacceptable. why was he not subpoenaed? he is the only named witness!

this obviously made no sense and the fact that only democrats were adamantly demanding the subpoena of judge and/or an fbi investigation before voting to confirm shows us a lot about how sick our politics are and how shockingly little so many players in that system value women and how disinterested they are in truth.
only after two brave sexual assault survivors confronted @jeffflake in an elevator, as he could barely make eye contact, did he later demand an fbi investigation.
thank you to the survivors who stood in the gap for us and demanded more from our government. i stand with you. ✊

you can find a link to this post in my bio. it's heavier than most, but i don't go into details of my assualt as i didn't want to trigger anyone.
if you feel called to share your story, comment below. let's hold space for one another 💖

336562;instagram;2018-09-29 15:46:09;TRUE;;"“... wasn’t original enough.”
what an insane editorial standard in the case of sexual assault.
never mind that it’s so common. it needs to have an angle to be worth mentioning?
infuriating.
thank you for sharing, jennifer, and i hope the boy-turned-quasi-man feels chastened this week.
#repost @jenniferniven with @get_repost

when i was writing my high school memoir in 2008, i wanted to include the story of a survived assault and the aftermath that followed— my fear in speaking up because of threats and the false and hurtful stories he spread— but a female at the publishing house told me it “wasn’t original enough.” she said it was a story that “every girl has lived to some degree,” that we’ve all heard it, and that for those reasons we should leave it out. but it happened to me. it impacted me. and if so many other women—and men— have experienced the same thing, shouldn’t we be talking about it more, not less? so i fought to keep it in. what they ultimately published was a watered down version. years later that boy— then a grown man— cornered me at a reunion and asked if he was the one in the book. he just didn’t know “what the fuss was about” and hoped i would be “over it by now.” thank you to everyone who speaks up and out and who uses your voice so that others don’t have theirs taken away. thank you to all the brave and beautiful souls who are out there fighting. 🌹 this lovely art by @tylerfeder is available to buy from her etsy shop, with all proceeds going to @rainn 🌼💫 together we can make a difference. 🦋#speakupsaturday #drchristineblaseyford #believesurvivors #useyourvoice #metoo #timesup #neverthelessshepersisted #ibelieveyou";en;#Repost, #drchristineblaseyford, #believesurvivors, #useyourvoice, #metoo, #timesup, #neverthelessshepersisted, #ibelieveyou;@jenniferniven, @get_repost, @tylerfeder, @rainn;;;;0;;beth4158;Beth Kujawski;;0;False;0;0;0;17;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/e48a544c8c0b5acaeb4c7ac8948b41d0/5D1E6DAC/t51.2885-15/e35/41648410_691480544565338_1744077815249164674_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"“... wasn’t original enough.”

yo te aseguro que cada mujer en el mundo que ha sido víctima de abuso sexual lo recuerda. está allí; con ella, todos los días de su vida. así funcione, trabaje, sonría, lleve a sus hijos al colegio, se vista bonito o decida no arreglarse más (porque ustedes saben la costumbre que hay de culpar a la victima por vestirse “provocativa”) esos recuerdos, ese trauma está ahí. así no se lo cuente a nadie, así no lo comparta, así lo guarde en lo más profundo de su ser, es real, existe.
l

existe, aunque años después no recuerde cada detalle, así no sepa como estaba vestido su agresor o el nombre y apellido de cada persona que vio ese día. saben que una de las maneras que tiene nuestro cerebro de protegernos del trauma es justamente hacernos olvidar? por eso aveces hay recuerdos parciales que no por eso dejan de ser reales. reales como las huellas, reales como la herida que un evento así causa en la vida de una mujer para siempre.
l

yo te creo, yo creo en ti. creo en que lo que te paso es real y se que te duele, se que es una jodida realidad a la que la sociedad nos ha sometido. por favor no sientas culpa. no sientas vergüenza. fuiste una víctima de abuso y aquí estás, te sobrepusiste o todavía estás tratando de sobreponerte. tu voz tiene altavoces, ya no es silente. con mujeres valientes como la dra. ford y miles más que se han armado de valor para hacerle frente a los cobardes que las agredieron, estamos cambiando la historia. como? una historia a al vez.
l

espero que todo lo que está pasando ahorita con kavanaugh, envíe un mensaje claro a los “niños” de 17 años y les enseñe que las consecuencias de sus actos duran para toda la vida y les explotará en la cara en algún momento. no hay más impunidad. nos unimos como mujeres, despertamos y nos vamos a proteger, vamos a hablar y vamos a denunciar. se acabo! 🙅🏻‍♀️🙅🏻‍♀️🙅🏻‍♀️

it was the end of my relationship. i found out my partner was cheating on me, so even though we still lived together we stopped talking.  i was still in a place where i was figuring out if i wanted to fight for the relationship.  after a month of no talking, we still slept in the same room, we still shared the same bed. one morning he got dressed for work. then got undressed, got back in bed and raped me while i pretended to sleep. then he left. it all happened in silence. .
three years ago.

i had a panic attack this morning. i have been crying since yesterday.  for some reason, getting dressed and making this post gives me peace. coming together with you, my friends. this amazing community of people, makes me feel better.  i will always look at the good, instead of the bad. i will always keep my mind open to love, not hate. but things happen to us.  we get damaged sometimes, and i’m realizing that some hurt never goes away. and that’s okay.  i want you to know that i love you, and i feel for you. i am holding your hand and sending you every bit of positivity energy i can, because you are not alone.  do not be ashamed. none of it was in your control.  you are still perfect in every, single way.

336605;instagram;2018-09-29 16:01:18;FALSE;"ana maria archila thank you.
i’ve been saying for more than a minute that women’s words move the world.
yesterday you showed us how.

#suchasmartask ""don't look away from me!"" look at me and tell me that it doesn't matter what happened to me, that you will let people like that go into the highest court of the land."" i’m both sorry and not that it took this.
i’m sorry because it’s seriously painful to be discounted and unheard. i think we all relived the pain of that with ford this week.
i’m not sorry because you demonstrated that if we are able to be someone we’ve never been before.... we can find the words and ways to have the conversations we’ve never been able to have before.
this is how we heal. this is how we build a new future.
yesterday you proved it true.
you didn’t back down. you wouldn’t be pushed aside.
you cried out loud for the world to see.
you made yourself heard... and in your doing so, i felt heard as well. i don’t know when my tears will stop, but i do know we must press on.
united in pain.
united is our desire to be seen, felt, heard.
and believed.
united in our knowledge that this shit has got to stop.
no matter how hard or unpleasant this week has been... humanity marches on.

336609;instagram;2018-09-29 16:06:27;FALSE;i have gone back and forth on sharing this so many times. do i want the world to know about some of the dark corners of my heart? would i get in trouble? because, yes, that is a real fear women have to face when coming forward with our stories. my heart still races thinking people would look badly on me.

i was 19. it was a night out with friends and there was underage drinking involved. i didn't know my limits and didn’t want to be seen as “lame”, plus i was with a guy i had been talking to for a little bit—so i was in good hands, right?

i fading in and out that night. parts were a blur, but i remembered coming home with that guy. later in bed with him. later finding myself having sex with him. i stopped it and went to bed. at least i think i did. the next morning i was confused as to what happened. i had my period and a tampon in, so i wouldn’t have had sex.

it wasn’t until later that next day when i told my roommate, if i don’t find that tampon we had to go to the hospital. everything came to fruition in the shower as i found the tampon that had been lost in me. i broke down. i became the 1 in 4 girls who was taken advantage of during college.
i blamed myself and justified him. i could’ve said yes. it wasn’t a big deal.
it wasn’t until i was talking with another male friend that he said regardless of what i had been like, if he was decent he wouldn’t have done that to you.

to this day i catch myself trying to brush it off and blaming myself for being in that position. when really, we as women should never have to worry about being taken advantage of or groped or raped. that should not fall on us. to all the women out there, you are not alone and we are stronger than what has happened to us. #metoo";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;liana_haven;Liana Christine;;0;False;20;0;0;71;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/0b3230f76c6e55c6beadb9b0dbc60e68/5D1418F2/t51.2885-15/e35/41870614_237385307135747_8316387288421453306_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i have gone back and forth on sharing this so many times. do i want the world to know about some of the dark corners of my heart? would i get in trouble? because, yes, that is a real fear women have to face when coming forward with our stories. my heart still races thinking people would look badly on me.

336614;instagram;2018-09-29 16:07:11;FALSE;"i’ve followed the #metoomovement since the beginning, watched so many brave women come forward with their stories. i’ve always felt like i didn’t need to say anything or share my experience because so many women did it for me. but then i realized my small voice added to those women makes a difference. i’ve watched and listened to the #kavanaughhearings and been shocked, angry, appalled, and heartbroken. i’ve listened to men say things like “why did she wait so long to say something” “he kept journals of his outings so he’s innocent,” as i listened to these men pick apart #drchristineblaseyford i had my own feelings of what happened when i finally said something. at 17 i was raped (not like in the movies, where it’s a total stranger) by a man that i knew, trusted to protect me from all harm. i hid what happened to me out of shame and embarrassment. a year later i said something and was questioned by a male police detective who kept asking me why i couldn’t remember every detail “i couldn’t possibly blackout everything” “why did i wait so long.” i let that man stop me from prosecuting the man that raped me. i let him make me believe that i was lying. this event in my life does not define me or make me who i am but changed how i see the world. why i #belivewomen who come forward, why i will say #timesup and #raisemyvoice to support all women.

“god purified them like gold in a crucible and found them as acceptable.”⠀
wisdom of solomon 3:6⠀
holy purifier,⠀
purify me!⠀
i long to be acceptable but not “appropriate.”⠀
following in your way is not a life dedicated to being nice and sweet.⠀
was jesus being “nice” when when he overturned the tables in the temple?⠀
all of life is a test-⠀
to deny this fact is be naive and foolish indeed.⠀
what shall i do?⠀
i must move towards truth-⠀
i must amplify the voices of women seldom believed.⠀
i believe.⠀
god knows.⠀
no more will we be silent.⠀
the god who is always with us can also say, “me too.”⠀
let us say it with the voice of divine thunder.⠀
let us overturn the tables of patriarchal tradition;⠀
let us purify our society until it passes god’s test.⠀
god is testing her people-⠀
are we passing?⠀
like job, we are right to put our troubles before god.⠀
like job, we can criticize those men who tell us we are at fault.⠀
like job, we will pass the test by pressing on,⠀
day by day, step by step, we will hold the men who abused us responsible⠀
god will put them in the kiln and we will hold then to the fire⠀

336623;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:00;FALSE;"“after all this time” is a performance about the incredible lengths victims must go to in the attempt to have their stories heard and believed — though those efforts are most likely futile. no matter how old or new an allegation, a survivor of assault will be made to doubt themselves and their story countless times in a circus of revictimization parading itself as justice. ◽

while “after all this time” is a performance, it is also a work of non-fiction. the camera follows the artist as she records the name of the man who assaulted her and then buries it in a time capsule as a futile insurance policy against future doubt. ◽
visit our story highlight “after all this time” to view an edited sequence of the full performance. ◽

336624;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:04;FALSE;"it’s been a hard, exhausting and emotional week. between the #kavanaughhearings and the anniversary of my own worst assault, part of me just wants to shut out the world and go to sleep for days. but then i remember that i am a survivor - i’m still here, breathing, living. i honor my need for rest, but i also owe it to myself to keep going and to thrive.

i know i’m not alone in feeling stirred up by these events this week. our collective pain and trauma has been triggered over and over again, and sometimes it feels like it will never end. but from our pain comes the courage so many have shown in speaking out and creating change. we will not break, and we will not be silenced.

if you are a survivor of sexual assault, harassment or abuse - i see you, i hear you, i believe you. it is not your fault, and you are not alone. remember to be kind and gentle with yourself - take a break from the news, go for a walk, reach out to a trusted loved one. and if you need any extra support, leave a comment or send me a message, i have tons of resources!
xox
[photo: from spring in chicago] 🖤

336626;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:57;FALSE;"this week has been difficult for so many of us.
but what it did for me was give me hope that we are opening up broader conversations, maybe even listening to women, even if it’s just a little bit more than we did before the #metoo movement began.

i’ve witnessed a lot of courageous, brave, heroic, patriotic acts this week from women like dr. ford and ana maria archila and marie gallagher (the elevator women who confronted senator flake). but where does this leave our kids? the next generation of victims and rapists?
will they know that no means no? will they know personal boundaries? will they feel safe enough to report it? will they listen better than we have?? so much worry.

dylan and i spent a good amount of time this week talking about consent and only touching others when they want to be touched, asking permission and giving permission- from a hug, to a kiss, to play fighting, to tickling, all of it.
so, after this exhausting week, i’m thankful for the conversation this opened up for me and my son. i have full confidence that our kids will be better than us, better than all of this.
we have to remember to look within our own scope of possibilities to make a difference, within our own 4 walls. we have to start small and hope that the reach is big.
but for those who went big this week, sharing your stories, i want to say...thank you. so much empowerment swelling, rising up. it’s beautiful and hard and sad and triggering and real and raw.
and it’s important that we are talking.
keep talking. they’ll have no choice but to listen.

336627;instagram;2018-09-29 16:10:58;FALSE;"my daughter was harassed at school the other day 💔 the night before, she carefully made sure she was following the dress code by not wearing shorts that were too short, straps that weren't too skinny on her tank top, and no midriff showing. she felt so proud and confident in her self expression and creative fashion statement! she looked so great that i even took her picture that morning! when i picked her up early to go get her braces, she walked up completely deflated, holding back tears... 'you look like you're in a strip down group'.
'why are you wearing that'?
'you're showing too much skin'.
'you're dressed real sexual'.
your outfit is inappropriate'.

these are the comments she received throughout the day from the boys in her class. assault/rape culture is perpetuated by complacency and ignorance. its as if the adults of the world are plugging their ears with their fingers, closing their eyes, shouting 'la la la la la...can't hear you...'. flash forward a few years, and guess who's now moved on from snide little comments in the fourth grade to cornering girls in the high school hallways, pushing them into bedrooms, and locking the doors? its the same boys, who grow to be sorry excuses of adult boys who lie, and gaslight, and deny their sickening behaviors. frankly, i'm appalled and ashamed and disappointed- like many millions of others. .

shame on anyone who actually believes that cutting words like the ones my daughter suffered in hearing are 'just things kids say', as if they aren't calculated and aimed to harm. im still waiting for a reply to the email i sent the principle. im taking names. i will file police reports. i will fight for my daughters and sons. we don't turn the other cheek in this family. #metoo my loves, #metoo

336644;instagram;2018-09-29 16:18:24;FALSE;"#metoo began as a movement that was meant to empower those in minority groups to speak up and own their rights to be and feel safe no matter what.
the original intention was to give voice to those in the minority.
and so this is not just a women’s movement as men and boys who have been molested, raped and sexually manipulated are deep in the minority and have to have our support in order to be heard.
how do we expect to see change in our men if we are mass vilifying and condemning them and at the same time not giving them a voice?
the point is to unite both men and women, both non minority and minority groups.  the point is to gain universal understanding, compassion and healing.
yes. me too.
i was molested by three people that i “should” have been able to trust: my music manager, my chiropractor and a someone who was giving me a pedicure at a salon on rodeo drive (not kidding).
then numerous other accounts of complete strangers aggressively groping me in clubs and on busses and subways.
with strangers it’s easier;  you know it’s wrong immediately, you scream and you fight.

with people you know or “should” be able to trust for some reason the psyche goes into shock and you end up spending the entire time debating whether it’s actually happening or not and questioning whether it was your fault and whether you “got yourself into this.”
and then there’s a point when you kick into #survivalmode and you purposefully don’t fight or make a scene so that you can get out alive and hopefully with the least amount of damage done.
that’s the problem right there - those crucial moments when the mind goes into shock instead of fight or flight.

those moments are the moments that a purpetrator can misread as a green light and ultimately can rationalize in their own mind that it’s okay. when if they were to listen to their intuition they would know that it’s not.

the progress forward to me is not “no means no.” because, #duh.  the progress forward is that “univited means univited.” there shouldn’t be a sexual advance without a verbal invitation (unless it’s in an already established relationship).

336656;instagram;2018-09-29 16:20:58;FALSE;"i’ve seen so many supportive posts these last few days a long with those that want to condemn those that were abused. i am grateful that the supportive ones have rang louder. if you are reading this and have a story to share just as i do there are some things i want to tell you... i may not know you but i love you!

when others may have told you it was your fault. i’m here to tell you it was not your fault!
when you begged for someone to believe you only to be called a liar or ignored... i believe you!
when you feel no one knows your pain...i share it with you!
when it seems that no one supports you family, friends, and even law enforcement...i support you!
you are beautiful!!
you are strong!!
you are worthy!!
you are loved!!
you are a survivor!! you are not alone!!!

as a woman who’s been sexually assaulted (in india no less) reporting is a very personal choice that every woman is faced with. .
i reported the predator who assaulted me and every step of that process was traumatic and prohibited me from healing, processing, and releasing the experience. .
it would have been so much easier if i didn’t report. .

i was victim-blamed, discouraged from filing a police report, had to change accommodations, be escorted home, and was put through numerous other inconveniences because of someone else’s choice to assault me. .
i didn’t do it for any other reason than to help protect other women. .
women don’t report for ourselves. .
we do it for other women. .

336660;instagram;2018-09-29 16:22:00;FALSE;"hello again friends.

it’s been heavy times for me personally, but i think for all of us as women. i posted a video to stories. i was planning to share it in june when i was really struggling, but it felt too raw. the video alludes to my experience as a woman and what i hope will be a different story for my daughters.

our formative experiences shape us, and they’re not always perfect. as adolescent women, so many of us grow to an understanding that our bodies are not built for ourselves. rather, they are built for a heteronormative standard that so many men have chosen to exploit.
it’s no surprise that women are coming forward and sharing their stories of sexual assault.

in late august, 2017, when i made the first of a half-dozen calls to @rainn, the national sexual assault hotline, sexual assault wasn’t a matter of public discourse. this was only a year ago, but it was before #metoo, before #drchristineblaseyford. before we understood that as women we have immutable rights and boundaries that are so often violated.
all i knew in that summer of 2017 is that something had happened to me which caused me great physical and emotional pain. and i knew that i needed help.

after months of effort, i entered the twilight zone better known as the american legal justice system. separately, i began to probe the depths of my childhood and adolescence through intensive therapy. i immersed myself in authors who could help explain things in plain language: germaine greer, rupi kaur, roxane gay, rayya elias, cheryl strayed, maya angelou, naomi wolf….

and just as i began to learn a sense of self-acceptance and nurture the child inside who carries so much shame, fear and anger…the world around me changed. our struggle as women became something that we could talk about out loud. something that we had every right to be angry about.

i have a lot of hope for the future. a year ago i didn’t. but that’s what it’s like to live on an island. a place of internal struggle so deep, so repressed, so un-talked about, that it has the force to bring about physical illness, to which i am no stranger.

i know that we’re better than this, i see the tides changing, and i am grateful.";;en;#metoo,, #DrChristineBlaseyFord.;@Rainn,;;;;0;;feedmedearly;Jessica Fiorillo;;0;False;163;0;0;1081;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/6baf47650f5c0493852e769d8de7f140/5D2249CE/t51.2885-15/e35/41763516_1079734788873625_806019579634651248_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"hello again friends.

i have a lot of hope for the future. a year ago i didn’t. but that’s what it’s like to live on an island. a place of internal struggle so deep, so repressed, so un-talked about, that it has the force to bring about physical illness, to which i am no stranger.

336663;instagram;2018-09-29 16:22:11;FALSE;"“we are diamonds, taking shape.” —

being in berlin has me reflecting a lot about walls, borders, glass ceilings, and all we are doing as a movement to break them down, all the while creating the world we seek to live and thrive in. from refugee resettlement to sexual violence to all the intersections in between, from dc to berlin, from my experience to yours, i see you, i hear you, i believe you, i honor you. and i love you, so fiercely. i so often wonder when they will be tired of fighting us, of hurting us, of using us, of seeing through us. but then i remember how much i continue to fight myself, to tell myself that my experience is invalid, and to push people away from helping me to create this world i so desperately desire to be a part of. it’s been a really hard week, but in the end we have one another and we hold one another, and in each other’s arms know that we are free. we are diamonds. ❤️
🎤”adventure of a lifetime”, coldplay.
📸 @natalie.paulina

🎤”adventure of a lifetime”, coldplay.

336684;instagram;2018-09-29 16:29:40;FALSE;"we are birthing a new world. we are birthing a new world and these are our labour pains. hear our screams. the new world has no room for anyone who thinks that sexual assault is ok. it has no room for those who pity the oppressor and look down upon the brave who stand up without anything to gain and everything to lose. the new world will not support the mistreatment of women, immigrants, people of color, lgbtqi or any other minority. we are breathing deeply, stacking our kindling and preparing the pyre. this time the witches do the hunting.
our men, the true ones among us, are those who know that we are equal in power. our power is very different but it is most definitely equal. and our power is fierce. you had better believe us.

for all woman who feel unheard, for all whose traumas have been triggered, for those currently living through violence and assault, for those who are waiting in hope for something to change and for us to be acknowledged and respected please know that you are heard and believed and loved and held.
the time is coming. good men and women and all those who do not identify with binary labels get ready.
we rise up together. we rise up with love. you had better believe us.
now please vote in the mother fucking midterms. please!!!!!!!!!!!!

to all the people who speak up against the violent act of sexual assault and sexual harassment, we got this! keep that vishuddha throat chakra active. this society has a long way to go and our fight will strengthens us.

336697;instagram;2018-09-29 16:31:38;FALSE;"#whyididntreport cw: abusive relationship. sexual content.
i was in a relationship and the role of girlfriend. so i didn't think it ""counted"". my body was used in ways that i said ""no"" to, and it resulted in medical intervention and trauma.

i was manipulated, isolated, belittled. thrown, tossed and grabbed. i had to do things to get things. or ""there were plenty other women [he] could give it to"". i though it was my fault for being weak. that if i wasn't so weak, none of it would happen. so, my own fault.

i am an open book, i share my stories in hopes of ending stigma, and providing strength and solidarity. this is the one topic i shut out of my own mind. i don't include it in conversations of healing. nopeitsoverimfine.
i still feel dirty and ashamed at his name.
no more. i am stronger. we are stronger. we are together in this.

men do not get to protect each other, or brush off their actions as ""locker room"" moments. if ""not all men"", then be better. get angry with your sisters. publicly. rally your ""good men"", and help us.
his name is pierre. he was someone in the canadian military and he abused and threatened me. in every sense of the word.
i am healing. i am ok.
i am whole. my body healed and my soul is safe.

i was manipulated, isolated, belittled. thrown, tossed and grabbed. i had to do things to get things. or ""there were plenty other women [he] could give it to"". i though it was my fault for being weak. that if i wasn't so weak, none of it would happen. so, my own fault.

i am an open book, i share my stories in hopes of ending stigma, and providing strength and solidarity. this is the one topic i shut out of my own mind. i do not include it in conversations of healing. nopeitsoverimfine.
i still feel diy and ashamed at his name.
no more. i am stronger. we are stronger. we are together in this.

men do not get to protect each other, or brush off their actions as ""locker room"" moments. if ""not all men"", then be better. get angry with your sisters. publicly. rally your ""good men"", and help us.
his name is pierre. he was someone in the canadian military and he abused and threatened me. in every sense of the word.
i am healing. i am ok.
i am whole. my body healed and my soul is safe.

336698;instagram;2018-09-29 16:31:39;FALSE;"i’ve lived alone a long time. six years spent in apartments with flimsy latches and thin aluminum-lined windows, burnt out porch lights and broken deadbolts. but i’ve never felt scared to live alone like i am now. never woken up in the middle of the night clutching at damp sheets, never slung scarves over curtainless windows or jammed long wooden dowels into frames.

i can’t help but associate these new damp palms and startled jumps with the way the world feels right now. we have me too and christine blasey ford and voices that are yelling loud and clear—but no one’s listening. it’s that moment in your dreams when you scream but no one hears, where you run but don’t move.

today i feel puny, helpless, unheard. but i also feel inspired—by the women who have been so gutsy and relentless, who keep pushing at a patriarchy that has roots dug deep into our world. it’s you, ladies, that have me pulling the curtains back today, unlatching the door, slinging the windows wide. we might be scared, but it’s our resilience in the face of that fear that makes us brave.
let’s keep marching.

day 91 of #100daysofselfcare

this week has been full of triggers for those of us who experienced sexual assualt. we may have discovered wounds that we have thought were healed still require our intention. some of us may have found that we had suppressed an experience similar to dr. ford's and her testimony brought it to the foreground.

the triggers may have been for other individuals who may have knowingly or unknowingly caused someone trauma. not sure what the consequences may be, how the person was traumatized, or how to sit with all that is going on.

the truth is we as a community we are coming to terms with the fact that we all are victims of rape culture. some of us sit in the middle in a neutral position but many of us sit at one of the extreme ends of the spectrum.
we need a lot to process this all-admission , apologies, forgiveness, detox, therapy and much more.
believing someone does not change the system. action does.
action on multiple levels.
as we navigate it all and find the process we need to heal make sure you take breaks from media, people, and things that bring you to unhealthy space.
it doesn't help.
protect your mind, body, and spirit.
it's a lot.
i know because i have been challenged by it for the better part of my life.
there are good days.
there are bad ones
there is breakthroughs
there is progression
remember who you are,
who you want to be, and your purpose.
love and light
nzingah . .

336722;instagram;2018-09-29 16:41:57;FALSE;"this week was raw, gut-wrenching, inspiring, heartbreaking and emotionally charged. this week was also a powerful reminder of how we can reclaim and fully stand in our feminine power. so where do we go from here? my takeaways:

stop apologizing for who you are. it's so easy to get trapped in cycles of self-blame, doubt and questioning our decisions. standing in your authentic truth means not letting anyone make you feel any less than who  you are or casting doubt or confusion when you know you are right.

speak, shout and broadcast your truth. it's not enough to just show up authentically. if you see something that's wrong, say it. speak up for women who don't have a voice. share your own experiences of injustice. share your story so that others will have the courage to also speak their truth. start conversations about consent with your neighbors and children.

love yourself and your body. you can be as sexual as you want. you can hang out in your swimsuit all day long. celebrate your body. love it. don't ever let yourself be defined by what society or men dictate to be the ""perfect"" body. create your own standards and remember that your  self worth comes from within.

build a bridge for other women. this week has forced me to take a hard look at how i'm supporting my sisters and women facing economic and social injustice all over the world. remember that there are still places in this world where women are killed for speaking their truth and standing up for what's right. let's stand by them.

i could go on and on but if nothing else, this week has helped me see how powerful our stories are when we come together. how are you feeling  after this week? ------------------------------------------

336739;instagram;2018-09-29 16:52:19;FALSE;"tonight. we are stars.

a starless night seemed apt for how i feel at this time. for my brain makes its own stars, like a concussion and migraine and i've been punched in the face ten times and have fallen to the ground and hold my head.
to be triggered is to have a starless night. everything around you turns dark suddenly, quickly, and yet your mind is so bright you do not need the stars in the sky to illuminate your path.
to illuminate your path you have the moon of trauma glare down, the sun behind it beats you with flashbacks and you do not need stars in the sky, the star of the show is your post traumatic stress.

it seems apt that today would be a starless sky, as words fly and other people's trauma resurfaces, and we must band together. be the stars. illuminate the path for those who cannot do it alone. we should not do it alone.
tonight is a starless sky.
tonight we band and make the stars.
watch us. blazing balls of fire.
tonight we are the stars in the sky. - k.h

336741;instagram;2018-09-29 16:52:21;FALSE;"these past few days have felt like an emotional rollercoaster… its taken me days to put it into words. like so many other survivors of sexual trauma, i have relived my own experiences as i watched dr. ford muster all of her courage and strength to speak her truth on a world-wide stage for all to see. it felt like riding the heavy and relentless waves of deep sadness, fear, anger, rage, shame, frustration, hopelessness… and then the spark of grief that inspired my own courage and bravery to rise within me.

dr. ford… thank you for showing us with your words and your actions what courage and bravery look like in a world when the deck is stacked against you. despite the risks to yourself, your family and your future, you did it anyways… you gave a voice to all survivors who have been shamed, guilted, doubted into silence.
despite the outcome… we will continue to heal… and we will continue to rise… and we will do it together.

to all survivors… i believe you… this was never your fault… you never need to doubt yourself… your gut knows the truth even though many may doubt you or minimize your experience… you don’t need to fight to prove it… your pain is your proof… your pain is real... it is just as real as your strength, your courage and your power to heal yourself from the inside out.
i stand with you… for you… and in service to you in your healing journey.

336747;instagram;2018-09-29 16:53:19;FALSE;"i'm only sharing this this extremely personal experience because this is a crazy time. in the wake of the #metoo movement and now kavanaugh i've been aware of it or not. it is a different time. maybe my story will help people understand why victims of assault don't come forward right away but it doesn't make their story untrue or not relevant. i was a virgin in college waiting to meet a nice guy that was worth the time. i partied, i was always around men, but always felt i had a handle. until one night we had a party. i woke up the next morning after what ended up being a black out night in a pool of my own blood naked with some dude next to me. i only knew him to be a friend of a friend. i didn't know what to do. i immediately started to blame myself. i drank too much. was i flirting? i must have lead him on? i continued to blame myself as i cried in the shower as he yelled ""bye"" through the door while leaving. what did i do to myself? turns out nothing. maybe i drank and flirted but it does not give a right for someone to take advantage of another while black out drunk. you'd think all the blood would be a hindrance. i let this go, and it def gave me issues i had to work through the years thankfully i never had to really see him again. he prob is married w/ kids and career now. maybe he's matured and never hurt another again. i'm not going to take the time to search him down and get at him for what happened now. however if he became a public figure, was running for a public office, or say appointed to be a supreme court justice, you better believe i'd speak up. a person of power in the public eye that has influence over our public, should be held accountable for anything they have done in the past as even a view of their nature, morals. even to have the ability of admittance with remorse and humility instead of passing blame would show some decency. i don't want the ""so sorry""s from sharing this i want this to help others understand victims' perspective.";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;cindope;Cindy 336798;instagram;2018-09-29 17:12:25;FALSE;before instagram existed (yeah, i’m getting old) in 2006, i participated in something called the clothesline project. this project is for female survivors of all types of abuse. the way it works is you get a t-shirt and write anything you want about the abuse you endured on it. you can even write your perpetrators first name if you want. then, the shirts are collected and hung on display on clotheslines in public places for people to view. this is the original “#metoo” movement. the end result is so powerful.  it changed my life, it made me feel so empowered to tell my truth for all the world to see. i got this tattoo to remind myself of how important it is to speak out against abuse and always tell the truth. the blue and green shirts signify that i am a survivor of child sexual abuse and incest. if you like this project, it’s still ongoing (yeah, over a decade later) and you can still participate today! find out more at 336810;instagram;2018-09-29 17:13:57;FALSE;even when we think we've healed something, an experience is presented that seems to bring it all back up. does it mean we're back at square one and all our progress has vanished? no.
we can learn to see this as an opportunity to heal different aspects of our trauma, because it's really these neglected aspects that are causing the resonant experience of triggering.
each day, i work with women (and a few men!), focused on healing. self-healing is my most intense passion.

this week, i've learned even more deeply to embrace flow. to say to myself ""it's ok that i'm not perfectly healed (that does not exist!) it's ok that i'm in pain. it's ok that i've neglected my trauma of sexual abuse because i was focused on deeply healing other personally more intense traumas."" i hear so many lovely people in this community talk about ""clearing"" experiences and energy as though we just burn some sage and boom! i've definitely used this term before too so it's all good. 😂 but we all know it's not like that.
the truth is that things don't just ""clear"", they heal. we have the ability to transmute energies of trauma and pain into love.
am i healed? yes. am i still healing? yes.
embrace the pain. heart wide open.
love to you and thank you for being here. thank you for loving and healing yourself. through healing ourselves, we'll heal the world. 💕

336825;instagram;2018-09-29 17:16:07;FALSE;the sheer number of stories i’ve read in the past four days of kids, children, teens, and adults being sexually assaulted is heart wrenching. i know, from personal experience, that not everyone tells someone right away. i have two #metoo stories. thank god, both were singular incidents. i know women (and men) have much more horrific tales to tell. one story was very much like dr. ford’s. i remember who it was. where i was. a lot of those details. the other story i was much younger. i think i know who it was, but i can’t be sure. i know where we were, and i know what he did. this is the only time i’ve ever really talked about either one of those. i’ve never told anyone in depth the entire story. that doesn’t mean i’m lying and it doesn’t mean it didn’t happen. we need to do better. raise your kids better. raise your sons better. i dare you, men, to sit with a woman, and ask her what steps she takes to protect herself. what does she think when she leaves a building at night alone? does she carry her keys in hand as a weapon? does she look in her back seat to see if anyone is there? does she think about where to park, and where not to park? does she avoid running or walking alone? etc. etc. for most women, this is daily routine. we need to do better. for all of our daughters and sons, we need to do better. #rtv #randomtalkingvideo 336842;instagram;2018-09-29 17:24:37;FALSE;"that’s my story. i’ve cried for the last two hours because of a meme. i finally told some of my family (now everyone). we all will see different sides of every single story and have our opinions. if we could share those with more kindness and understanding i’m sure the world would be a better place. please don’t ever falsely accuse someone. you may ruin their life, but you make it that much harder for a true victim to come forward.

i am proud to be a part of a very timely piece of theatre that is going up in october! - link in bio!
a timely twist on the shakespearean classic, mary v is a timely reflection on #metoo, women’s anger, and how we decide who gets to occupy public space.

an all-female cast has been commissioned to perform shakespeare’s henry v. but when they arrive at the rehearsal space, they discover their show has been given to a traditionally male-dominated cast. both groups believe that the play rightfully belongs to them. mirroring the conflict at the heart of shakespeare’s original script, the two casts go to battle for their show, raising vital questions about gender, leadership and violence along the way. ""mary v” first premiered as part of the dream up festival with theater for a new city on august 28, 2016. it was co-produced by theater for a new city for an off-off broadway run in june 2017. this october, it will run for the third time as part of the new york international fringe festival.";;en;#ibelieveher, #metoo,;;;;;0;;baigray;Bailey Gray;;0;False;1;0;0;38;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/421f2ea17e13fe6fdf2029d759452a3d/5D1A02BD/t51.2885-15/e35/42490952_154176212192689_6896665142178039844_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"art is so important right now.

336873;instagram;2018-09-29 17:38:31;FALSE;"sitting in the dark this morning + hiding from my dad’s family upstairs, because they have a habit of congratulating me on my podcast in one breath and supporting kavanaugh and trump in the next. it’s very casual to them that we “disagree on politics,” but i can’t seem to scream #metoo loud enough for anyone to care to rethink whether dr ford has the right to voice her experience, let alone if maybe what happened to her matters more than a man’s career.

every time my dad tells me he doesn’t know if his high school self would live up to today’s standards i want to scream at him that he should apologize for that, not laugh about it, but i always “get emotional” and am dismissed and then everyone acts like nothing happened.

after trump’s election, i decided that one of the best things i could do with my privilege is to stand up to my family and stop letting their bullshit slide, but it’s been an exhausting two years of battling them, and this week has hit so close to home that i can barely muster the strength for that fight.
i say all of this here now, because i am so thankful for this beautiful community that i can carry in my pocket and feel seen by when i need it.

y’all are a true lifeline of much-needed support and care for survivors everywhere who are isolated from communities who understand for whatever reason. i really never thought facebook and instagram posts mattered so much, but i get it now, and they really do. thank you for your words and your love and please keep spreading it around. i see you. i believe you. 🖤";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;ladyameliaa;a m e l i a;;0;False;16;0;0;81;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ee12d330f15090a56abefb3781b34386/5D104ED2/t51.2885-15/e35/41669104_296931481136851_6512014105400144087_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"sitting in the dark this morning + hiding from my dad’s family upstairs, because they have a habit of congratulating me on my podcast in one breath and supporting kavanaugh and trump in the next. it’s very casual to them that we “disagree on politics,” but i can’t seem to scream #metoo loud enough for anyone to care to rethink whether dr ford has the right to voice her experience, let alone if maybe what happened to her matters more than a man’s career.

336876;instagram;2018-09-29 17:39:13;TRUE;;"it’s been a long week full of emotions and opportunities to process and heal. transparency moment- i’m not that girl. the one who is willing to talk about the things that happened. i’m not ready to name names and share my story (in that way). i’ve become a master at healing certain parts of myself but not so successful at addressing this. atleast not fully...but that doesn’t make me less of a healer, less brave, less...period.
and so today i’m taking a step back. i’m taking the time to address my hurt for myself. i am committed to healing all parts of self and holding space for others to do the same.
to the women who still hurt, who still live in fear..who aren’t ready to talk i see you. i believe you. i love you.
#heyhollis #healingmatters #selfcare #selflove

336902;instagram;2018-09-29 17:54:17;FALSE;"***please read ***

as a woman, i have grown tired of striving to be less...to eat less, to dumb myself down, to weigh less, to grab the pink weights and lift less, to do everything...less. after finding fitness, and an amazing community of strong and empowered women, i learned to strive to be more. to go harder, to lift heavier, to be stronger, to be a fucking power house of fierceness! with all the kavanaugh stuff on the news i felt the need to share my feelings. i'm not going to share my story, as i don't find it necessary to do so. i will, however, share how i deal...why i do what i do...in hopes of inspiring others do do the same. pushing myself to my limits physically is empowering. it makes me feel safe. it makes me feel strong.
here's a workout dedicated to the pain and suffering you may have dealt with in the past, at the hands of someone else. .
round one is dedicated to the times you blamed yourself.
round two is dedicated to the times you felt no one would belive you.
round three is dedicated to the times you convinced yourself it wasn't a big deal. .
round four is dedicated to the times you felt guilt, anxiety, and stress.
round five is dedicated to the times you pretended nothing happened.
round six is dedicated to the amazing strength you now have, to the amazing woman you have become. .
now dust yourself off, because you are a fucking bad ass fighter. i believe you. i believe her. #metoo .
tag a friend who could use the support.

as a woman, i have grown tired of striving to be less...to eat less, to dumb myself down, to weigh less, to grab the pink weights and lift less, to do everything...less. after finding fitness, and an amazing community of strong and empowered women, i learned to strive to be more. to go harder, to lift heavier, to be stronger, to be a fucking power house of fierceness! with all the kavanaugh stuff on the news i felt the need to share my feelings. i am not going to share my story, as i do not find it necessary to do so. i will, however, share how i deal...why i do what i do...in hopes of inspiring others do do the same. pushing myself to my limits physically is empowering. it makes me feel safe. it makes me feel strong.
here's a workout dedicated to the pain and suffering you may have dealt with in the past, at the hands of someone else. .
round one is dedicated to the times you blamed yourself.
round two is dedicated to the times you felt no one would belive you.
round three is dedicated to the times you convinced yourself it wasn't a big deal. .
round four is dedicated to the times you felt guilt, anxiety, and stress.
round five is dedicated to the times you pretended nothing happened.
round six is dedicated to the amazing strength you now have, to the amazing woman you have become. .
now dust yourself off, because you are a fucking bad ass fighter. i believe you. i believe her. #metoo .
tag a friend who could use the support.

society tends to place blame and shame on the wrong individuals. i’m not sure how we change this when the people in charge sometimes are the perpetrators, refuse to believe victims or aren’t empathetic. for that reason, reporting is very dangerous.
we can start by acknowledging this does happen though.
if you ignore it, you are part of the problem.

336923;instagram;2018-09-29 17:59:12;FALSE;"i know most of you are sick of this topic, but i’m not because it’s affecting so many and it’s part of my purpose. when we can look at what is happening in our world, on both sides, and not be triggered or defensive, we know we have begun the healing journey. i’m starting a private fb group for sexual assault survivors, their loved ones, and fellow healers -both men and women, republican or democrat-because i understand why survivors feel the need to be heard. trust me, i know firsthand that anger and rage have their place in the beginning stages of healing. but this will not a place to rally, rant , or conspire, but rather a safe space to share and heal.
dm me if you would like to be added.
it’s time to heal our collective wounds and move forward towards victory!❤️#victory *

i typically offer these two items once a year in the early spring but in wake of the trauma so many of us have had to relive these last few days (and often everyday in our society), i wanted to make these two items available. proceeds will be donated to organizations that support victims of sexual assault and we will not turn anyone away who is seeking aid and needs financial assistance. we have had people generously offer to cover costs of those who need these allies the most and i myself am dedicated to ensuring that you get the support you need right now. this offer goes beyond these two items – i have many products for emotional well-being. if you need them, send me a message. if you aren't sure what would be best for you, send me a message 💜⠀⠀

336932;instagram;2018-09-29 18:07:10;FALSE;the actions of our legal system and national press have brought on a deep melancholie for women this week.
it has been even more upsetting than donald trump being elected for president of our country.
it has been as upsetting as the myriad of attrocities of #blacklivesmatter
we are dealt massive blow after massive blow.
for most women, this trial has solidified an awareness of a lifetime of slow-burning, passive oppression caused by men in our lives. both personally and proffessionally.
women have been in the trenches for centuries getting stronger and stronger without losing our core strength.
we are motherhood.
the gender & race civil movents are joining at the hip and the fight is strong.
don’t kavanaugh on us gentlemen.

336939;instagram;2018-09-29 18:09:09;FALSE;"we made it to saturday, friends. now i want to share why it was so demoralizing to listen to the conversation surrounding dr. christine blasey ford’s testimony about judge kavanaugh this week. •

i don’t know many women who have not been sexually assaulted. many of us have been raped. some of us have been pressured to do things with bosses that we didn’t want to do. most of us have been groped. all of us know we move through the world, every day, with the awareness that we are not physically safe. •

for decades, many of us thought we were the only one, or we confided in two or three friends who, we found out, also happened to have similar stories. we blamed ourselves. had we been too friendly? maybe we didn’t resist hard enough? we didn’t try to knee them in the groin because we hadn’t taken those self-defense classes so instead we just checked out and laid there—it must’ve been our fault, we thought. •

then #metoo happened and we learned we weren’t alone. this had actually happened to most women! there wasn’t something toxic about us that made us targets; there was something wrong with our society and the story men were told about what they could do to women’s bodies. people became aware of the pervasiveness of sexual violence against women in our society, and with awareness would come change, we thought.

then this week happened. we saw two responses to credible claims of sexual violence that devastated us: 1.) people didn’t believe the women—said they were making it all up. 2.) they believed the women and they didn’t care. we learned that we can make people aware, but we can’t make them care, and that some people relish the opportunity to put credibly accused sexual offenders in the highest positions of power in our country. we heard that our stories and our bodies didn’t matter. our trauma was a mere inconvenience to a man’s path to power.

so we did what we’ve always done: we gathered in small groups, hopped on text threads, checked in, and lifted each other up. we told our stories again, to people who saw us, people who believed us, people who cared. that’s how we’ll go on surviving: we’ll do it together. and hopefully, we’ll remake the world together.";;en;#metoo;;;;;0;;julie_rodgers;Julie Rodgers;;0;False;18;0;0;267;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/b3595f06e8f231c9812d0fe5a88cba9b/5D1539EF/t51.2885-15/e35/41734862_1880276282054965_8156278688824550328_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"we made it to saturday, friends. now i want to share why it was so demoralizing to listen to the conversation surrounding dr. christine blasey ford’s testimony about judge kavanaugh this week. •

336964;instagram;2018-09-29 18:22:44;FALSE;"i wrote this many years  ago but it has never rang more true. dark, yes, for it needs to be. #metoo -
all the silent girls.
i realize now
decades later
they were the abused ones,
the misused ones,
the girls in the back seats of cars,
willing, hungry, any attention would do.
the ones boys called,
with a self-satisfied wink:
easy,
when what they were was
lost.
most of them i lay you odds,
struggling for air
under the thumb, the boot,
of a distant father, sinister uncle,
stern boyfriend.
silent,
for none would listen.
silent,
for whom would believe.
all the sad girls, the voiceless girls,
carrying unseen yokes on
their frail backs
to the end of their days,
then down,
powerless,
down
into their uneasy graves. -

before instagram existed (yeah, i’m getting old) in 2006, i participated in something called the clothesline project. this project is for female survivors of all types of abuse. the way it works is you get a t-shirt and write anything you want about the abuse you endured on it. you can even write your perpetrators first name if you want. then, the shirts are collected and hung on display on clotheslines in public places for people to view. this is the original “#metoo” movement. the end result is so powerful.  it changed my life, it made me feel so empowered to tell my truth for all the world to see. i got this tattoo to remind myself of how important it is to speak out against abuse and always tell the truth. the blue and green shirts signify that i am a survivor of child sexual abuse and incest. if you like this project, it’s still ongoing (yeah, over a decade later) and you can still participate today! find out more at http://clotheslineproject.info/  #clotheslineproject #weareher #survivor";en;#Repost, #clotheslineproject, #WeAreHER, #survivor;@_weareher, @get_repost;;;;0;;turningpointinc;Turning Point;;0;False;3;0;0;22;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/c048005427287fe842d7bdf3c390b0fd/5D1E4B1E/t51.2885-15/e35/41669117_294269227838736_6522447683073089811_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"#repost @_weareher with @get_repost

336981;instagram;2018-09-29 18:26:27;FALSE;"when we first heard about trump and weinstein, and the #metoo movement started to gain momentum, i’m pretty sure that we in the u.k. felt a collective sense of “not again”.

you see, in 2012, we began to see accusations being made against men of the same age range. the baby boomers. the accusations were first made against a once beloved man who raised millions for charity, jimmy savile. it’s said that his victims number between 300-400. he was a prolific sexual predator who used his celebrity and well respected status to gain access to children and young women. people who were vulnerable due to not only their age but in some cases, their disabilities. he had free range of numerous hospitals and care homes, tv audiences made up of starstruck youngsters, children who were part of the criminal justice system and more. some people did report his crimes and they were not believed because “jimmy does a lot for charity”. when the truth came out about him, he had already been dead for a year. the truth was revealed in a tv documentary. it shook the nation but at the same time, many of us had already had an unsettling feeling about him.

in the wake of these awful accusations, more and more men from the same era were accused of sexual assault to varying degrees. many of them were celebrities; gary glitter, max clifford, dave lee travis, rolf harris, and more. aside from gary glitter, we were all shocked. these were men we had all grown up with. national treasures. child friendly entertainers. other men who weren’t famous were also accused including a doctor at one of the hospitals jimmy savile spent a lot of time at. the bbc came under heavy fire as being an organisation that enabled and hid these crimes.

initially, some people asked why the victims hadn’t come forward sooner. they were accused of wanting money or attention. they were accused of lying. most of these comments were made by people who were also part of the baby boomer generation. it seemed that back then, it just happened and you didn’t talk about it. if a man wanted to pat a woman’s bottom, that was perfectly acceptable. bosses could kiss their secretaries. children had to sit on laps when told.
